1
00:00:00,480 --> 00:00:07,200
Random entries, random exits, random 
results. This is why you fail. This  

2
00:00:07,200 --> 00:00:13,200
video is a professional trading blueprint. 
It shows you the right path step-by-step,  

3
00:00:13,200 --> 00:00:18,560
whether you've placed 1,000 trades 
or you're a complete beginner.

4
00:00:18,560 --> 00:00:20,960
Let's start with market structure.  

5
00:00:20,960 --> 00:00:27,280
Market structure refers to the overall map of 
the market, the patterns of highs and lows,  

6
00:00:27,280 --> 00:00:33,760
and the price swings connecting them over time. 
If you look at any price chart, you'll see the  

7
00:00:33,760 --> 00:00:40,080
market structure laid out before your eyes—the 
static record of how price moved in the past.

8
00:00:40,080 --> 00:00:45,280
When prices keep rising or falling, 
that creates a trend. In an uptrend,  

9
00:00:45,280 --> 00:00:51,920
each new high is higher than the last one. We call 
that a Break of Structure (BOS). At the same time,  

10
00:00:51,920 --> 00:00:57,520
each low stays above the previous low 
point. That bullish momentum continues  

11
00:00:57,520 --> 00:01:02,960
until the price finally dips below a 
prior major low, which is a Change of  

12
00:01:02,960 --> 00:01:08,000
Character (CHoCH). You can tell a trend is 
losing steam when the price fails to make  

13
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:14,800
a new high after the latest rise. That's 
a sign buyers may be losing their grip.

14
00:01:14,800 --> 00:01:21,280
In a downtrend, you'll see the opposite: 
lower lows and highs that can't quite reach  

15
00:01:21,280 --> 00:01:27,680
the last high. This bearish pressure from 
sellers keeps pushing the price down. The  

16
00:01:27,680 --> 00:01:34,320
trend stays in place as long as those lower 
highs and lows keep coming. But if the price  

17
00:01:34,320 --> 00:01:40,400
manages to top the last high, the trend 
could be reversing to bullish territory.

18
00:01:40,400 --> 00:01:47,040
Sometimes the market takes a breather and moves 
sideways between trends. This happens when the  

19
00:01:47,040 --> 00:01:54,800
highs and lows are roughly equal, creating a tight 
range. We call this a consolidation period. The  

20
00:01:54,800 --> 00:02:00,720
price stays stuck, bouncing between supply 
and demand until it finally breaks out above  

21
00:02:00,720 --> 00:02:08,240
the usual highs or below the normal lows of that 
channel. That's when a new trend could be born.

22
00:02:08,240 --> 00:02:14,240
For a trend to flex its muscle, it needs 
to keep printing those new highs and lows.  

23
00:02:14,240 --> 00:02:20,640
But only one candle testing highs doesn't mean 
much. If you see several candles close above  

24
00:02:20,640 --> 00:02:27,200
past resistance in a row, that's a stronger case 
for buyer control. And the reverse is true for  

25
00:02:27,200 --> 00:02:35,120
downtrends: a few candles breaking below support 
strengthens the argument for seller dominance.

26
00:02:35,120 --> 00:02:41,600
Another thing to watch is how far each new swing 
travels. If every price leg is bigger than the  

27
00:02:41,600 --> 00:02:49,440
last, this tells you the dominant force is gaining 
momentum with every cycle. The growing imbalance  

28
00:02:49,440 --> 00:02:56,160
between supply and demand is fueling increasingly 
larger price movements. So, even if the market  

29
00:02:56,160 --> 00:03:03,520
has entered a sideways phase, seeing progressively 
larger waves suggests the current bigger trend may  

30
00:03:03,520 --> 00:03:12,080
still be healthy. Speed matters, too. A swift move 
to new highs or lows over fewer candles is more  

31
00:03:12,080 --> 00:03:20,320
powerful than a gradual climb or descent. It's a 
sign of intensifying pressure driving the price.

32
00:03:20,320 --> 00:03:26,640
Trading is all about finding edges, and support 
and resistance levels are one of the most powerful  

33
00:03:26,640 --> 00:03:33,680
edges you can have. But these invisible lines 
on your charts can make or break your trades.  

34
00:03:33,680 --> 00:03:38,880
Basically, support and resistance are 
price levels where the market tends  

35
00:03:38,880 --> 00:03:46,960
to pause or reverse. Support is an area that 
catches falling prices. Resistance is an area  

36
00:03:46,960 --> 00:03:52,320
that stops prices from rising further. 
And it's all about supply and demand.

37
00:03:52,320 --> 00:03:59,760
At support, buyers step in. They see the price 
as a bargain and start buying. At resistance,  

38
00:03:59,760 --> 00:04:06,320
sellers take over. They think the price is 
too high and start selling. Here's the key:  

39
00:04:06,320 --> 00:04:13,280
these levels aren't exact prices. They are more 
like zones where interesting things happen.

40
00:04:13,280 --> 00:04:18,960
But why should you care about support and 
resistance? First, they help you understand  

41
00:04:18,960 --> 00:04:26,000
market structure. You can see where price is 
likely to pause or reverse. This knowledge is  

42
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:33,760
gold for timing your entries and exits. Second, 
these levels show you where other traders are  

43
00:04:33,760 --> 00:04:40,560
placing their orders. Big players often cluster 
their orders around support and resistance. And  

44
00:04:40,560 --> 00:04:48,080
when you know where the big money is, that's your 
edge. We'll talk about that later. Third, support  

45
00:04:48,080 --> 00:04:55,280
and resistance levels are self-fulfilling. Traders 
expect price to react at these levels, so they  

46
00:04:55,280 --> 00:05:02,720
place their orders accordingly. This collective 
action makes those areas even more interesting.

47
00:05:02,720 --> 00:05:09,280
Now, let's dive into the minds of buyers and 
sellers at these key price points. At support  

48
00:05:09,280 --> 00:05:15,440
levels, buyers tend to step in, seeing the 
price as a good deal. They believe the price  

49
00:05:15,440 --> 00:05:22,240
is undervalued and expect it to rise from this 
point. This buying pressure often causes the  

50
00:05:22,240 --> 00:05:29,360
price to bounce off support. At resistance 
levels, sellers become more active. They view  

51
00:05:29,360 --> 00:05:35,840
the price as too high and anticipate a drop, 
leading to increased selling pressure. This  

52
00:05:35,840 --> 00:05:43,040
behavior creates a self-fulfilling prophecy. As 
more traders watch these levels and act on them,  

53
00:05:43,040 --> 00:05:49,120
their collective actions make the levels 
more likely to hold, at least temporarily.

54
00:05:49,120 --> 00:05:53,520
Market memory plays a crucial 
role in shaping these zones.  

55
00:05:53,520 --> 00:05:59,920
Traders remember past price levels where 
significant buying or selling occurred. These  

56
00:05:59,920 --> 00:06:07,040
memories influence future trading decisions. The 
concept of "trapped traders" also contributes to  

57
00:06:07,040 --> 00:06:12,960
market memory. Imagine a trader who bought 
at a certain price only to see the market  

58
00:06:12,960 --> 00:06:19,920
drop. He might be eager to sell at breakeven 
when the price returns to his entry point.  

59
00:06:19,920 --> 00:06:26,000
This creates resistance as these 
trapped traders exit their positions.

60
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:33,840
Support and resistance zones often form around 
round numbers ending in zero or double zeros.  

61
00:06:33,840 --> 00:06:39,120
This is partly due to the psychological 
comfort we find in round numbers. Many  

62
00:06:39,120 --> 00:06:44,800
traders place orders at these levels, 
creating natural support and resistance.

63
00:06:45,360 --> 00:06:50,800
The strength of support and resistance 
levels can change over time. A level that's  

64
00:06:50,800 --> 00:06:56,880
been tested multiple times without breaking 
becomes more significant in traders' minds,  

65
00:06:56,880 --> 00:07:03,360
but it also becomes more likely to eventually 
break as more traders are watching it and  

66
00:07:03,360 --> 00:07:09,600
positioning themselves around it. When a 
support or resistance level does break,  

67
00:07:09,600 --> 00:07:16,720
the ensuing price move can be dramatic. This is 
because many traders place their stop-loss orders  

68
00:07:16,720 --> 00:07:22,800
just beyond these levels. When the level 
breaks, it triggers a cascade of orders,  

69
00:07:22,800 --> 00:07:29,440
accelerating the price move. This behavior 
is often exploited by large market players  

70
00:07:29,440 --> 00:07:35,680
who might push the price through a level to 
trigger these stops before reversing the move.

71
00:07:36,480 --> 00:07:42,720
High-quality support and resistance levels have 
several special traits that make them stand out  

72
00:07:42,720 --> 00:07:48,960
on a chart. One of the most prominent features 
of strong levels is the presence of sharp,  

73
00:07:48,960 --> 00:07:54,720
big reversals. These are points on the 
chart where the price makes a sudden and  

74
00:07:54,720 --> 00:08:00,640
significant change in direction. For 
example, if price is falling rapidly  

75
00:08:00,640 --> 00:08:06,720
and then suddenly bounces back up just as 
quickly, this sharp reversal could indicate  

76
00:08:06,720 --> 00:08:12,720
a strong support level. This dramatic price 
movement suggests that there's a significant  

77
00:08:12,720 --> 00:08:19,760
imbalance between buyers and sellers at 
these levels, leading to quick reversals.

78
00:08:19,760 --> 00:08:26,000
High-quality support and resistance levels often 
show multiple instances of price bouncing off  

79
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:32,720
them. This repeated behavior reinforces the 
importance of these levels. For instance,  

80
00:08:32,720 --> 00:08:37,760
if you notice that a stock price has 
bounced up from a level several times,  

81
00:08:37,760 --> 00:08:43,360
this could be an important support level. 
These multiple bounces demonstrate that  

82
00:08:43,360 --> 00:08:50,800
traders consistently recognize these levels and 
act on them, creating a self-fulfilling prophecy.

83
00:08:51,440 --> 00:08:57,200
Swing highs and lows are another important 
feature to look for because they represent  

84
00:08:57,200 --> 00:09:04,000
areas where the balance between buyers and 
sellers shifted significantly. High-quality  

85
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:11,280
levels often demonstrate the ability to act as 
both support and resistance. This characteristic,  

86
00:09:11,280 --> 00:09:17,680
known as role reversal, happens when a broken 
support level becomes a new resistance level,  

87
00:09:17,680 --> 00:09:23,600
or when a broken resistance level becomes a 
new support level. This phenomenon happens  

88
00:09:23,600 --> 00:09:29,440
because traders remember these levels 
and adjust their behavior accordingly.

89
00:09:29,440 --> 00:09:35,280
One of the key traits of high-quality support 
and resistance levels is that they are visually  

90
00:09:35,280 --> 00:09:42,720
obvious on a chart. These levels should stand 
out clearly even to an inexperienced trader. If  

91
00:09:42,720 --> 00:09:49,760
you have to squint your eyes to identify a level, 
it might not be as significant as you think. The  

92
00:09:49,760 --> 00:09:55,200
most powerful support and resistance levels are 
those that are immediately apparent when you look  

93
00:09:55,200 --> 00:10:02,400
at a chart. This visual prominence is important 
because it means that many traders are likely to  

94
00:10:02,400 --> 00:10:09,280
notice and act on these levels, increasing 
their potential impact on price movements.

95
00:10:09,280 --> 00:10:13,840
Support and resistance levels that 
have been recently respected tend to  

96
00:10:13,840 --> 00:10:20,400
be more reliable than older levels. This is 
because market conditions change over time,  

97
00:10:20,400 --> 00:10:25,680
and levels that were significant in the 
distant past may no longer be relevant.  

98
00:10:26,240 --> 00:10:30,880
Look for levels that have influenced 
price movements in the recent past,  

99
00:10:30,880 --> 00:10:37,760
as these are more likely to continue playing 
a role in current and future price action.

100
00:10:37,760 --> 00:10:45,280
Round numbers often act as psychological support 
and resistance levels. For instance, many traders  

101
00:10:45,280 --> 00:10:52,560
might set their take-profit orders at $100 if 
a stock is approaching that level from below,  

102
00:10:52,560 --> 00:10:58,560
or they might set stop-loss orders just 
below $100 if the stock is trading above  

103
00:10:58,560 --> 00:11:06,640
it. This clustering of orders around numbers can 
create noticeable support and resistance effects.

104
00:11:06,640 --> 00:11:13,200
The strongest support and resistance levels 
typically combine multiple traits. For example, a  

105
00:11:13,200 --> 00:11:20,320
level might be a round number, have acted as both 
support and resistance in the past, show multiple  

106
00:11:20,320 --> 00:11:27,760
bounces, and be easily visible on the chart. The 
more of these characteristics a level exhibits,  

107
00:11:27,760 --> 00:11:33,760
the more likely it is to be a significant support 
or resistance point. And when drawing support  

108
00:11:33,760 --> 00:11:40,160
and resistance lines on your charts, remember 
that they don't always need to be exact. Prices  

109
00:11:40,160 --> 00:11:47,520
can sometimes break slightly past these levels 
before reversing (known as a false breakout), or  

110
00:11:47,520 --> 00:11:54,320
they might reverse direction just before reaching 
the level (an imperfect reversal). So, you might  

111
00:11:54,320 --> 00:12:01,680
need to draw a wider zone rather than a precise 
line to capture all the relevant price action.

112
00:12:01,680 --> 00:12:07,360
Now, before we continue, let us know in the 
comments what topics you'd like us to cover.  

113
00:12:07,360 --> 00:12:10,960
Please tell us what you want to watch next.

114
00:12:10,960 --> 00:12:17,360
Now, let's talk about support and resistance 
flips. When price breaks through a support level,  

115
00:12:17,360 --> 00:12:24,720
it shows a shift in power from buyers to sellers. 
The former support level then often becomes a  

116
00:12:24,720 --> 00:12:30,960
new resistance level. This happens because 
traders who bought at a support level and  

117
00:12:30,960 --> 00:12:38,320
are now facing losses may sell when the price 
returns to that level, creating resistance.  

118
00:12:38,320 --> 00:12:44,480
When price breaks above a resistance level, 
that level can become a new support level,  

119
00:12:44,480 --> 00:12:49,600
as traders who missed the initial move 
up may buy at the former resistance,  

120
00:12:49,600 --> 00:12:55,280
now viewing it as a good entry point. 
These flips demonstrate the psychological  

121
00:12:55,280 --> 00:13:01,440
aspects of trading. Traders remember price 
levels where significant shifts occurred,  

122
00:13:01,440 --> 00:13:07,440
and their collective actions around these 
levels can create self-fulfilling prophecies.

123
00:13:07,440 --> 00:13:14,480
The strength of these flipped levels often depends 
on how decisively the original level was broken.  

124
00:13:14,480 --> 00:13:20,640
A strong, high-volume break of a support or 
resistance level is more likely to result in  

125
00:13:20,640 --> 00:13:26,880
a reliable flip than a weak break on low 
volume. The number of times a level has  

126
00:13:26,880 --> 00:13:33,840
acted as support or resistance in the past 
also influences its strength after a flip.  

127
00:13:33,840 --> 00:13:40,480
A level that has been tested multiple times 
before breaking is often more significant.

128
00:13:40,480 --> 00:13:46,720
When a support or resistance level is broken, 
wait for a retest of that level before entering  

129
00:13:46,720 --> 00:13:54,080
a trade. If a former support level holds as new 
resistance (or vice versa), it can confirm the  

130
00:13:54,080 --> 00:14:02,000
breakout. Sometimes a level will fail to hold 
after flipping. For example, a broken support  

131
00:14:02,000 --> 00:14:08,640
level might not hold as resistance. These failed 
flips can lead to strong moves in the opposite  

132
00:14:08,640 --> 00:14:16,240
direction as traders who were counting on the 
level holding are forced to exit their positions.

133
00:14:16,240 --> 00:14:22,720
When trading support and resistance flips, 
consider the overall market context. In strong  

134
00:14:22,720 --> 00:14:30,080
trends, flipped levels are more likely to hold, 
while in choppy or ranging markets, they may  

135
00:14:30,080 --> 00:14:38,080
be less reliable. Volume can provide additional 
confirmation. High volume on the initial break and  

136
00:14:38,080 --> 00:14:45,440
again on the retest can increase the likelihood 
of a successful flip. And it's also important to  

137
00:14:45,440 --> 00:14:52,800
note that not all support and resistance levels 
will flip cleanly or hold after flipping. The  

138
00:14:52,800 --> 00:14:59,200
market is dynamic, and even strong levels 
can be broken under the right circumstances.

139
00:14:59,200 --> 00:15:04,960
One powerful aspect of support and resistance 
flips is that they often mark the beginning  

140
00:15:04,960 --> 00:15:12,800
of new trends. When a long-standing resistance 
level is finally broken and then holds as support,  

141
00:15:12,800 --> 00:15:19,200
it can signal the start of a significant 
uptrend. When a strong support level breaks  

142
00:15:19,200 --> 00:15:24,800
and then acts as resistance, it might 
indicate the beginning of a downtrend.

143
00:15:25,600 --> 00:15:31,840
Volume is a key tool in trading support and 
resistance. It's like a secret code that  

144
00:15:31,840 --> 00:15:37,520
reveals the strength of these levels. When 
you mix volume with price action, you get a  

145
00:15:37,520 --> 00:15:44,880
powerful method called Volume Price Analysis. As 
you already know, not all levels are the same.  

146
00:15:44,880 --> 00:15:52,160
Some are strong and some are weak. And how do you 
know which is which? That's where volume comes in.

147
00:15:52,160 --> 00:15:57,920
Think of volume as the fuel that drives the 
market. When there's a lot of volume at a price  

148
00:15:57,920 --> 00:16:05,280
level, it means there's a lot of interest there. 
This can create strong support or resistance. The  

149
00:16:05,280 --> 00:16:11,760
Volume Profile tool is great for finding these 
key levels. It shows you where most trading  

150
00:16:11,760 --> 00:16:18,480
happened. The areas with the most volume are 
often important support and resistance zones.

151
00:16:18,480 --> 00:16:23,600
When you look at a volume profile, 
focus on three main levels. First,  

152
00:16:23,600 --> 00:16:28,960
the Point of Control (POC). This is where 
most trading occurred. It's often a strong  

153
00:16:28,960 --> 00:16:36,560
support or resistance level. Then, the Profile 
High. This can act as resistance. And lastly,  

154
00:16:36,560 --> 00:16:44,240
the Profile Low. This can act as support. These 
levels matter because they show where buyers and  

155
00:16:44,240 --> 00:16:50,960
sellers were most active. They're like battle 
lines where the big players fought over price.

156
00:16:50,960 --> 00:16:57,920
When price nears a key level, watch the volume 
closely. If price breaks through with high volume,  

157
00:16:57,920 --> 00:17:02,960
it's often a real breakout. But if 
it breaks through with low volume,  

158
00:17:02,960 --> 00:17:11,120
it might be a fake-out. On the flip side, if price 
touches a level and bounces off with high volume,  

159
00:17:11,120 --> 00:17:18,160
that's a strong rejection. It means the level 
held firm. But if it bounces with low volume,  

160
00:17:18,160 --> 00:17:21,680
the level might not be as strong as it looks.

161
00:17:21,680 --> 00:17:28,880
Here's a cool trick: when price makes a big move 
away from a level, use the Volume Profile to see  

162
00:17:28,880 --> 00:17:35,200
where the most trading happened during that 
move. That spot often becomes a new support  

163
00:17:35,200 --> 00:17:42,320
or resistance level when price returns to it 
later. Let's say you see a big price drop.  

164
00:17:42,320 --> 00:17:49,840
You can put a volume profile on that drop to find 
where the most trading occurred. That area might  

165
00:17:49,840 --> 00:17:57,200
become resistance when price rises again. If 
it does, it could be a great place to sell.

166
00:17:57,200 --> 00:18:04,080
Remember, the market moves in waves. It trends 
for a while, then pauses in a congestion phase,  

167
00:18:04,080 --> 00:18:10,240
then either keeps trending or reverses. 
Understanding how volume works with these  

168
00:18:10,240 --> 00:18:16,720
moves is key to reading the market. When you're 
looking at a potential trade, don't just look  

169
00:18:16,720 --> 00:18:23,680
at the price. Check the volume, too. Is it above 
average? That's a sign of strength. Is it below  

170
00:18:23,680 --> 00:18:30,160
average? That might mean the move is weak. If 
you're thinking about buying at support, look  

171
00:18:30,160 --> 00:18:37,520
for high volume as price touches that level; that 
shows strong buying interest. If you're thinking  

172
00:18:37,520 --> 00:18:44,800
about selling at resistance, look for high volume 
there, too. That can mean strong selling pressure.

173
00:18:44,800 --> 00:18:51,840
As we already talked about, false breakouts and 
liquidity runs are common traps in trading. When  

174
00:18:51,840 --> 00:18:57,200
price breaks through a key level, don't 
just jump in right away. Wait for volume  

175
00:18:57,200 --> 00:19:02,960
to confirm the move. A true breakout 
should come with above-average volume.  

176
00:19:02,960 --> 00:19:08,880
And if volume is low, it might be a 
fake-out. But here's a cool trick:  

177
00:19:08,880 --> 00:19:15,280
sometimes a failed breakout can be an even 
better trade. If price breaks out on low  

178
00:19:15,280 --> 00:19:23,360
volume and then quickly reverses, that can be a 
strong signal to trade in the opposite direction.

179
00:19:23,360 --> 00:19:29,120
Don't forget about timeframes. What looks 
like a breakout on a 5-minute chart might  

180
00:19:29,120 --> 00:19:36,160
just be noise on a daily chart. Always check 
higher timeframes to get the big picture before  

181
00:19:36,160 --> 00:19:42,880
making your decisions. Learning to read volume 
in conjunction with support and resistance takes  

182
00:19:42,880 --> 00:19:50,480
practice, but it's worth the effort. You'll see 
trading opportunities you never noticed before.

183
00:19:50,480 --> 00:19:54,880
Trading support and resistance will 
differ considering if the markets are  

184
00:19:54,880 --> 00:20:00,320
trending or they are ranging. And most 
traders don't think about this aspect,  

185
00:20:00,320 --> 00:20:05,920
which is a major mistake. In a strong 
trend, support and resistance levels  

186
00:20:05,920 --> 00:20:11,600
can help you catch big moves. When the 
market is trending up or down with force,  

187
00:20:11,600 --> 00:20:18,320
it's not wise to fight it. Instead, look 
for ways to join the trend at good prices.

188
00:20:18,320 --> 00:20:24,000
Here's how to use these levels in 
a strong uptrend. As price climbs,  

189
00:20:24,000 --> 00:20:30,960
it will often pause and drop back a bit. These 
dips often stop at old resistance levels which  

190
00:20:30,960 --> 00:20:38,320
now act as support. Sometimes price will move 
sideways for a while. This is like a pause in the  

191
00:20:38,320 --> 00:20:45,840
trend. It can form a small range near a support or 
resistance level. Watch for breakouts. When price  

192
00:20:45,840 --> 00:20:51,440
breaks above the high of the consolidation, 
it can signal the trend is ready to continue.

193
00:20:52,400 --> 00:21:00,160
In a strong downtrend, you'd use the same ideas 
but in reverse. Look for bounces from resistance,  

194
00:21:00,160 --> 00:21:04,560
consolidations, and breakdowns below support.

195
00:21:04,560 --> 00:21:09,760
Ranging markets are trickier. Price bounces 
between support and resistance without a  

196
00:21:09,760 --> 00:21:16,000
clear direction. Here's how to use these 
levels. First, identify the range. Look  

197
00:21:16,000 --> 00:21:22,720
for clear areas where price has turned multiple 
times. Wait for tests of these levels. As price  

198
00:21:22,720 --> 00:21:27,920
approaches support or resistance, watch 
closely. How it acts here can tell you  

199
00:21:27,920 --> 00:21:35,360
a lot. You then look for rejection signals. If 
price touches support and bounces up with force,  

200
00:21:35,360 --> 00:21:42,320
it might be a good time to buy. If it hits 
resistance and drops hard, consider selling.

201
00:21:42,320 --> 00:21:50,240
Be cautious of false breakouts. Price often pokes 
above resistance or below support only to reverse.  

202
00:21:50,240 --> 00:21:56,640
Look for wicks or multiple wicks outside the 
range. Watch for consolidations near the top  

203
00:21:56,640 --> 00:22:03,840
or bottom of the range (a consolidation within 
the consolidation). If price forms a tight range,  

204
00:22:03,840 --> 00:22:10,080
it can signal a potential breakout. Of 
course, use volume. High volume on a  

205
00:22:10,080 --> 00:22:18,400
bounce off support can signal a strong move. Low 
volume might mean the move is weak. In ranges,  

206
00:22:18,400 --> 00:22:25,040
you're often looking to buy near support and sell 
near resistance, but be ready to change your view  

207
00:22:25,040 --> 00:22:32,800
if the range breaks and a new trend starts. And 
consider the timeframe. Levels on a daily chart  

208
00:22:32,800 --> 00:22:41,280
might not match what you see on a 5-minute 
chart. Be clear about your trading horizon.

209
00:22:41,280 --> 00:22:48,480
In the market, there are always two competing 
forces: buyers, who represent demand, and sellers,  

210
00:22:48,480 --> 00:22:54,640
who represent supply. When there are more 
buyers than sellers at a certain price level,  

211
00:22:54,640 --> 00:23:00,720
it creates a demand zone. When there are 
more sellers than buyers at a price level,  

212
00:23:00,720 --> 00:23:06,960
it forms a supply zone. In these zones, 
you often see large unfilled orders from  

213
00:23:06,960 --> 00:23:13,280
big institutional traders like banks and 
hedge funds. Supply and demand trading is  

214
00:23:13,280 --> 00:23:19,600
powerful because it allows you to trade in line 
with what the institutions are doing. These big  

215
00:23:19,600 --> 00:23:25,520
players can't hide their massive orders. 
And by identifying supply and demand zones,  

216
00:23:25,520 --> 00:23:31,600
retail traders like us can spot where they 
are likely to be executing their trades.

217
00:23:31,600 --> 00:23:37,840
You see, the price is constantly moving up and 
down, and this movement is a direct result of the  

218
00:23:37,840 --> 00:23:43,600
supply and demand from market participants. 
When there are more buyers in the market,  

219
00:23:43,600 --> 00:23:50,320
they bring demand, and this applies upward 
pressure on prices, pushing them higher. When  

220
00:23:50,320 --> 00:23:56,720
there are more sellers, they bring more supply to 
the market, putting downward pressure on prices  

221
00:23:56,720 --> 00:24:03,920
and pushing them lower. This dynamic between 
buyers and sellers is what we call Order Flow,  

222
00:24:03,920 --> 00:24:09,360
and it's the engine that actually 
drives price action and market movement.

223
00:24:09,360 --> 00:24:14,160
Now, there are two main types of 
orders that make up this order flow:  

224
00:24:14,160 --> 00:24:21,280
passive orders and aggressive orders. Passive 
orders are limit orders placed by traders who  

225
00:24:21,280 --> 00:24:26,320
are willing to wait for the price to come to 
their desired level. They are not in a rush to  

226
00:24:26,320 --> 00:24:32,800
get in. Aggressive orders are placed by traders 
who want to execute immediately at the current  

227
00:24:32,800 --> 00:24:40,240
market price. They are not waiting around for a 
specific price; they want in fast. This constant  

228
00:24:40,240 --> 00:24:45,920
battle between passive and aggressive orders 
is really what causes those explosive price  

229
00:24:45,920 --> 00:24:52,240
movements you see on your charts when there's a 
significant imbalance between supply and demand.  

230
00:24:52,240 --> 00:24:58,960
So, your job is to identify where 
major imbalances are likely to occur.

231
00:24:58,960 --> 00:25:04,720
Now let's break down how to actually identify 
them on your charts. The first step is to  

232
00:25:04,720 --> 00:25:10,400
look for those explosive movements where 
price makes a strong push in one direction  

233
00:25:10,400 --> 00:25:16,640
before quickly reversing. This could be 
a sharp rally followed by a sudden drop,  

234
00:25:16,640 --> 00:25:23,280
or a steep decline followed by a rapid bounce 
back. These movements often signal that there  

235
00:25:23,280 --> 00:25:30,160
was a significant imbalance between buyers 
and sellers that caused price to spike. Once  

236
00:25:30,160 --> 00:25:34,640
you've spotted one of these big moves, 
the next step is to mark out the origin  

237
00:25:34,640 --> 00:25:40,880
of that move—in other words, the area on 
your chart where that explosive rally or  

238
00:25:40,880 --> 00:25:46,880
decline actually started. This is going to 
be your potential supply or demand zone.

239
00:25:47,520 --> 00:25:52,800
Now, there are a few different types of 
zones to look out for. First ones are  

240
00:25:52,800 --> 00:25:59,440
Base Zones or Range Zones. These form when 
price is consolidating in a tight range for  

241
00:25:59,440 --> 00:26:04,960
an extended period of time before finally 
breaking out. You can think of the edges  

242
00:26:04,960 --> 00:26:12,160
of that range as areas of supply and demand 
where a lot of orders have built up. So when  

243
00:26:12,160 --> 00:26:18,640
price revisits those levels after a breakout, 
there's a higher probability of a reaction.

244
00:26:18,640 --> 00:26:24,000
We can also have Pivot Zones. These form 
at key turning points in the market,  

245
00:26:24,000 --> 00:26:30,880
like swing highs and lows, or where you see price 
making a sudden change in direction. They're often  

246
00:26:30,880 --> 00:26:37,600
marked by one or two candlesticks with distinct 
characteristics. For a potential demand zone,  

247
00:26:37,600 --> 00:26:44,160
you want to look for a strong bearish candle 
where the next candle closes back above its high,  

248
00:26:44,160 --> 00:26:50,400
signaling a shift from selling pressure 
to buying pressure. For a supply zone,  

249
00:26:50,400 --> 00:26:56,640
you are watching for a strong bullish candle 
where the next candle closes below its low,  

250
00:26:56,640 --> 00:27:03,040
indicating a shift from buying to selling. The 
key is that these pivots are happening quickly;  

251
00:27:03,040 --> 00:27:08,560
price isn't spending much time 
in these areas before reversing.

252
00:27:08,560 --> 00:27:14,000
To identify fresh zones, you also want to 
pay attention to the overall structure of  

253
00:27:14,000 --> 00:27:21,360
the price action. There are two main types of 
structures to look for: Continuation and Reversal.

254
00:27:21,360 --> 00:27:27,520
A continuation structure forms when there's an 
existing trend in place and price is just pulling  

255
00:27:27,520 --> 00:27:33,920
back or correcting against that trend before 
continuing in the same direction. These are your  

256
00:27:33,920 --> 00:27:41,440
Rally-Base-Rally and Drop-Base-Drop patterns. 
If it's an uptrend, you'll see a strong rally,  

257
00:27:41,440 --> 00:27:48,480
a tight range where price forms a small base, 
and then another rally continuing the uptrend.  

258
00:27:48,480 --> 00:27:56,640
For a downtrend, you'll see a sharp drop, a base, 
and then another drop, resuming the downtrend.

259
00:27:56,640 --> 00:28:02,960
Reversal structures form when price is reversing 
from one trend direction to the other. These are  

260
00:28:02,960 --> 00:28:10,800
your Drop-Base-Rally and Rally-Base-Drop patterns. 
So, in an uptrend that's starting to lose steam,  

261
00:28:10,800 --> 00:28:15,920
you might see price drop into a base 
and then launch into a new rally,  

262
00:28:15,920 --> 00:28:22,160
marking the start of a reversal. And in a 
downtrend that's starting to turn around,  

263
00:28:22,160 --> 00:28:30,000
you'd see a rally, a base, and then a strong 
drop signaling the beginning of a new uptrend.

264
00:28:30,000 --> 00:28:35,440
Now, let's talk about the key principles 
that make this strategy so effective.  

265
00:28:35,440 --> 00:28:41,360
The first thing to understand is that supply and 
demand zones are not just random levels on your  

266
00:28:41,360 --> 00:28:48,240
charts. They are areas where the imbalance 
between buyers and sellers is most extreme.  

267
00:28:48,240 --> 00:28:55,040
When you see explosive price movements like huge 
rallies or steep drops, that's often a sign that  

268
00:28:55,040 --> 00:29:01,360
there was a serious mismatch between the amount of 
buying and selling pressure. What's happening in  

269
00:29:01,360 --> 00:29:07,120
these situations is that the aggressive orders 
from one side are rapidly consuming all the  

270
00:29:07,120 --> 00:29:14,000
available orders from the other side until a new 
equilibrium is found. The areas on your charts  

271
00:29:14,000 --> 00:29:21,280
where these big clashes take place are what we 
call fresh unmitigated supply and demand zones.

272
00:29:21,280 --> 00:29:26,720
One of the key things that separates these 
high-probability zones from ordinary support  

273
00:29:26,720 --> 00:29:32,000
and resistance levels is the amount of 
time price spends in the zone. You see,  

274
00:29:32,000 --> 00:29:36,000
when there's a major imbalance 
between buyers and sellers,  

275
00:29:36,000 --> 00:29:42,640
the price won't hang around that area for very 
long. It will quickly spike up or down. So,  

276
00:29:42,640 --> 00:29:47,600
when you're analyzing your charts, one of 
the things to look for is zones where the  

277
00:29:47,600 --> 00:29:54,800
price only spent a short amount of time before 
making a strong move in either direction. The  

278
00:29:54,800 --> 00:30:00,160
less time price spends in that area, the 
more out of balance supply and demand are,  

279
00:30:00,160 --> 00:30:06,240
and the higher the probability of a successful 
trade when the price returns to that zone.

280
00:30:06,880 --> 00:30:12,960
Another key principle is to focus on fresh 
unmitigated zones rather than ones that  

281
00:30:12,960 --> 00:30:19,280
have already been tested multiple times. 
When price revisits a zone, it can absorb  

282
00:30:19,280 --> 00:30:25,680
some of the pending orders that were sitting 
there, making the imbalance less extreme. So,  

283
00:30:25,680 --> 00:30:32,960
as a general rule, the more times a zone has been 
hit, the weaker it becomes. This is why it's so  

284
00:30:32,960 --> 00:30:38,960
important to understand the difference between 
an unmitigated zone and one that's already been  

285
00:30:38,960 --> 00:30:46,880
tested a few times (a mitigated one). The trading 
opportunities are very different. Now, of course,  

286
00:30:46,880 --> 00:30:53,360
there are times when a zone can remain valid even 
after being tested if there is still a significant  

287
00:30:53,360 --> 00:31:00,640
order imbalance, but generally, you want to 
prioritize fresh zones when planning your trades.

288
00:31:00,640 --> 00:31:03,040
So, the key things to look for are:

289
00:31:03,040 --> 00:31:09,200
Zones that form after explosive price movements.
Zones where price only spends a short amount of  

290
00:31:09,200 --> 00:31:13,840
time before spiking up or down.
Fresh zones that haven't been  

291
00:31:13,840 --> 00:31:20,400
tested or absorbed by the market yet.
Now, let's talk about how to validate  

292
00:31:20,400 --> 00:31:26,320
whether a zone is likely to hold. The first 
thing you want to look for is a clear Break  

293
00:31:26,320 --> 00:31:32,480
of Structure (BOS). This means price needs 
to make a decisive move away from the zone  

294
00:31:32,480 --> 00:31:39,440
and take out any nearby swing highs or lows. 
If there's no clear break of structure and  

295
00:31:39,440 --> 00:31:46,400
price just hovers around the zone, that's a sign 
that the zone might not be as strong as it seems.

296
00:31:46,400 --> 00:31:52,560
Another key concept is the idea of Flip Zones. 
This is when a previous supply zone turns into  

297
00:31:52,560 --> 00:31:59,040
a demand zone, or vice versa. For example, 
let's say you have a strong supply zone  

298
00:31:59,040 --> 00:32:05,520
that's been holding price down for a while, but 
then suddenly price rips through that level and  

299
00:32:05,520 --> 00:32:12,160
closes above it. That's a pretty good indication 
that the zone has flipped from supply to demand  

300
00:32:12,160 --> 00:32:18,080
and could now act as a support level for 
future pullbacks. But here's the thing:  

301
00:32:18,080 --> 00:32:23,760
in order for a flip zone to be valid, you need 
to see that initial interaction between the two  

302
00:32:23,760 --> 00:32:30,560
forces. Don't just assume a zone has flipped 
because price moved past it. Look for that  

303
00:32:30,560 --> 00:32:38,800
clear battle between buyers and sellers and wait 
for one side to decisively overpower the other.

304
00:32:38,800 --> 00:32:44,240
Another important factor to consider is 
Inducement. This refers to the presence of  

305
00:32:44,240 --> 00:32:50,000
liquidity in front of the zone that could 
potentially absorb any move against it.  

306
00:32:50,000 --> 00:32:55,520
For example, if you're looking at a demand 
zone, you want to see some buy orders stacked  

307
00:32:55,520 --> 00:33:01,360
up in front of that level. This could be in 
the form of a swing low or a consolidation  

308
00:33:01,360 --> 00:33:07,520
pattern—anything that suggests there are 
traders waiting to buy at that price. If  

309
00:33:07,520 --> 00:33:12,400
there's no liquidity in front of the 
zone and price just slams into it,  

310
00:33:12,400 --> 00:33:17,920
chances are those big players aren't going to 
be too interested in getting involved. But if  

311
00:33:17,920 --> 00:33:24,400
there are orders they can trade against, they're 
much more likely to step in and defend the level.

312
00:33:24,400 --> 00:33:30,480
Of course, even if a zone checks all these 
boxes, it's not guaranteed to hold forever.  

313
00:33:30,480 --> 00:33:35,920
That's why it's also important to look 
at how fresh the zone is. In general,  

314
00:33:35,920 --> 00:33:39,680
zones that have been tested 
multiple times are less likely  

315
00:33:39,680 --> 00:33:45,040
to produce strong reactions than those 
that are being hit for the first time.

316
00:33:45,680 --> 00:33:51,120
Now let's talk about the difference between 
supply and demand zones and traditional support  

317
00:33:51,120 --> 00:33:57,920
and resistance levels. While there are similar 
concepts, there are some key distinctions. First  

318
00:33:57,920 --> 00:34:05,040
off, support and resistance are levels where 
price has previously reversed or consolidated  

319
00:34:05,040 --> 00:34:11,680
multiple times in the past. Supply and demand 
zones, on the other hand, are all about fresh  

320
00:34:11,680 --> 00:34:18,560
unmitigated levels. Rather than focusing on areas 
that have already been touched multiple times,  

321
00:34:18,560 --> 00:34:25,440
these zones represent imbalances between buyers 
and sellers that have just recently formed.  

322
00:34:25,440 --> 00:34:29,600
The key difference is that support 
and resistance trading relies on the  

323
00:34:29,600 --> 00:34:35,440
assumption that past levels will continue to 
hold in the future, whereas supply and demand  

324
00:34:35,440 --> 00:34:42,800
trading looks for new untested zones where the 
order flow is likely to be more significant.

325
00:34:42,800 --> 00:34:47,840
Remember this: support and resistance 
levels are essentially supply and demand  

326
00:34:47,840 --> 00:34:54,880
zones that have already been confirmed. Once 
a fresh demand zone gets tested and holds,  

327
00:34:54,880 --> 00:35:01,200
it then becomes an established support level. 
The same goes for supply zones; they become  

328
00:35:01,200 --> 00:35:07,520
resistance after they've been touched. So, while 
trading support and resistance can certainly be  

329
00:35:07,520 --> 00:35:13,600
effective (especially if a level has proven itself 
multiple times in the past), the probability of  

330
00:35:13,600 --> 00:35:20,960
a reaction tends to diminish with each subsequent 
test. This is why you should focus on fresh zones  

331
00:35:20,960 --> 00:35:28,240
where the initial imbalance between buyers and 
sellers is likely to be the most significant.

332
00:35:28,240 --> 00:35:34,400
Now, let's talk about some specific entry and 
exit strategies you can use around these key  

333
00:35:34,400 --> 00:35:40,960
levels. One of the simplest and most effective 
ways to enter a trade is to simply set a limit  

334
00:35:40,960 --> 00:35:46,640
order directly on the level itself. This 
approach assumes that the zone will hold  

335
00:35:46,640 --> 00:35:53,360
and that price will reverse once it hits your 
order. However, there are a couple of potential  

336
00:35:53,360 --> 00:35:59,200
downsides to this aggressive strategy. If you 
set your order too far away from the zone,  

337
00:35:59,200 --> 00:36:05,040
you might miss out on the trade entirely if 
price never quite reaches your price. Or,  

338
00:36:05,040 --> 00:36:10,400
the second scenario: price might just 
break through your zone with ease.

339
00:36:10,400 --> 00:36:15,840
A more conservative approach is to wait for 
a specific candlestick pattern to form at the  

340
00:36:15,840 --> 00:36:22,720
level before entering a trade. For example, 
you might look for a bullish reversal pattern  

341
00:36:22,720 --> 00:36:28,640
like a pin bar or an engulfing candle 
at a demand zone. The idea behind this  

342
00:36:28,640 --> 00:36:33,280
strategy is that these candlestick 
formations can give you a bit more  

343
00:36:33,280 --> 00:36:39,760
confirmation that the zone is likely to hold 
and that price is getting ready to reverse.

344
00:36:39,760 --> 00:36:45,200
Another technique you can use to fine-tune your 
entries is to look for specific structures on  

345
00:36:45,200 --> 00:36:51,920
lower timeframes. For example, let's say you've 
identified a strong demand zone on the 1-hour  

346
00:36:51,920 --> 00:36:58,240
chart, but you want to get more precise with 
your entry. Instead of just buying blindly at  

347
00:36:58,240 --> 00:37:04,240
the level, you could drop down to the 15-minute 
chart and look for a reversal pattern like a  

348
00:37:04,240 --> 00:37:09,920
double bottom or a Change of Character 
(CHoCH) to form at the zone. In this way,  

349
00:37:09,920 --> 00:37:15,600
you can often get a tighter entry 
with a better risk-to-reward ratio.

350
00:37:15,600 --> 00:37:21,920
Now, let's talk about how to evaluate the strength 
of a supply or demand zone. One of the first  

351
00:37:21,920 --> 00:37:28,720
things to look at is how quickly price moves 
away from the zone after it's formed. Generally  

352
00:37:28,720 --> 00:37:35,360
speaking, the faster price shoots away from a 
level, the stronger that level is likely to be.  

353
00:37:35,360 --> 00:37:41,600
Quick and significant moves away from a zone 
indicate a strong imbalance. So if you see  

354
00:37:41,600 --> 00:37:47,120
price just rocketing away from a zone, that's 
a pretty good sign that there is some serious  

355
00:37:47,120 --> 00:37:53,920
order flow happening there and that institutions 
are likely defending the level aggressively.

356
00:37:53,920 --> 00:37:58,960
Another factor to consider is the amount 
of time price spends at the zone before  

357
00:37:58,960 --> 00:38:04,240
making that initial move. The less 
time price hangs out at a level,  

358
00:38:04,240 --> 00:38:09,440
the more likely it is to be a key turning 
point in the market. So if you see price  

359
00:38:09,440 --> 00:38:15,040
just kind of dip into a demand zone and 
then immediately start rallying higher,  

360
00:38:15,040 --> 00:38:22,480
that's often a signal that big buyers have stepped 
in and are absorbing all the available supply.

361
00:38:22,480 --> 00:38:26,640
The actual size of the move 
is important, too. Obviously,  

362
00:38:26,640 --> 00:38:32,880
if price barely budges after hitting a supply 
or demand level, that's not exactly a big  

363
00:38:32,880 --> 00:38:38,160
endorsement of its strength. But if you see 
an extended move in the opposite direction  

364
00:38:38,160 --> 00:38:44,240
after a zone is tested, that's a sign that 
the level is probably pretty significant.

365
00:38:44,240 --> 00:38:50,560
Another thing to watch for is the volume during 
the formation of the zone. Generally speaking,  

366
00:38:50,560 --> 00:38:55,920
you want to see a noticeable uptick 
in volume as price is testing a key  

367
00:38:55,920 --> 00:39:01,280
level. This indicates that there's a lot 
of interest and activity happening at that  

368
00:39:01,280 --> 00:39:08,240
specific price and that institutions are 
likely absorbing or distributing there.

369
00:39:08,240 --> 00:39:13,760
Another factor that can affect the strength 
of a zone is whether or not it causes a break  

370
00:39:13,760 --> 00:39:19,920
of market structure. A supply or demand 
zone that causes a break of structure is  

371
00:39:19,920 --> 00:39:25,600
generally stronger. It takes a significant 
amount of money to break market structure,  

372
00:39:25,600 --> 00:39:32,160
making the zones more likely to hold in the 
future. So if you see a zone forms and then price  

373
00:39:32,160 --> 00:39:38,000
just starts trending in the opposite direction 
and breaking through key levels on the chart,  

374
00:39:38,000 --> 00:39:42,400
that's often a sign that there is some 
serious institutional backing behind the  

375
00:39:42,400 --> 00:39:48,240
move and that the zone is likely to 
be a key focal point going forward.

376
00:39:48,240 --> 00:39:53,520
When it comes to candlesticks, most price 
action books will advise you to memorize  

377
00:39:53,520 --> 00:39:59,760
a plethora of candlestick patterns or spend 
hours staring at charts. I'm going to give  

378
00:39:59,760 --> 00:40:04,800
you a better method to read them. First 
and foremost, when you open up a chart,  

379
00:40:04,800 --> 00:40:10,320
take a look at the recent candles and focus 
on their spread. The spread is the difference  

380
00:40:10,320 --> 00:40:16,480
between a candle's opening and closing price, 
which forms the real body of the candle.  

381
00:40:16,480 --> 00:40:22,320
This spread reveals the market sentiment for 
that particular time period. A wide spread  

382
00:40:22,320 --> 00:40:29,120
indicates strong market sentiment, while a 
low spread indicates less trading activity.

383
00:40:29,120 --> 00:40:33,040
Next, you look at the upper and 
lower wicks of candlesticks,  

384
00:40:33,040 --> 00:40:38,320
also known as shadows. These wicks reflect 
the buying and selling pressure in the  

385
00:40:38,320 --> 00:40:44,000
market. Consider them as rejection areas 
where the market simply didn't accept the  

386
00:40:44,000 --> 00:40:50,160
prices represented by the wick. The length of the 
wick, whether at the top or bottom of the candle,  

387
00:40:50,160 --> 00:40:56,080
should always be a main point of focus. It 
instantly reveals strength, weakness, or  

388
00:40:56,080 --> 00:41:04,080
indecision in the market. And most importantly, it 
shows you where buyers or sellers are stepping in.

389
00:41:04,080 --> 00:41:08,240
Now, considering the spread of 
the candlesticks and their wicks,  

390
00:41:08,240 --> 00:41:11,680
here are the key patterns you should consider.

391
00:41:11,680 --> 00:41:17,360
When the body of the candle takes up at least 
half of the entire bar range, you are looking  

392
00:41:17,360 --> 00:41:24,400
at a Trend Bar. Trend bars are the heart and 
soul of market fluctuations. They represent  

393
00:41:24,400 --> 00:41:30,960
strong market sentiment and suggest a likely 
continuation in the direction of the candle.  

394
00:41:30,960 --> 00:41:36,880
When you analyze a chart, pay attention to 
instances of consecutive trend bars closing  

395
00:41:36,880 --> 00:41:43,200
in the same direction. If you spot several trend 
bars in a row, all pointing in the direction of  

396
00:41:43,200 --> 00:41:49,360
the prevailing trend, it's a clear sign of 
strength in that direction. If you notice an  

397
00:41:49,360 --> 00:41:56,640
absence of trend bars over the past 10 or so 
candles, the market is likely consolidating.

398
00:41:56,640 --> 00:42:02,960
A Trend-Based Long Wick Candle is characterized 
by a candle with a wick sticking out in the same  

399
00:42:02,960 --> 00:42:08,640
direction as the moving trend. The smaller the 
body and the longer the wick, the better the  

400
00:42:08,640 --> 00:42:16,240
quality of the candle. Large wicks indicate price 
moved a lot during the candle but got rejected,  

401
00:42:16,240 --> 00:42:22,960
signaling supply or demand. The upper wick 
acts as resistance while the lower wick acts  

402
00:42:22,960 --> 00:42:30,400
as support. In an uptrend, if a long wick candle 
forms at a key support level, it means sellers  

403
00:42:30,400 --> 00:42:36,960
tried to push prices lower but failed to close 
with momentum, causing the wick to stick out.  

404
00:42:36,960 --> 00:42:42,480
This suggests a potential continuation of the 
previous trend. The length of the wick is the  

405
00:42:42,480 --> 00:42:49,440
first point of focus because it instantly shows 
strength, weakness, and indecision in the market.

406
00:42:50,000 --> 00:42:56,400
The Momentum Candle is characterized by a 
larger spread compared to the previous candles,  

407
00:42:56,400 --> 00:43:03,200
showing a clear directional movement in price. 
In an uptrend, you'll notice each candle getting  

408
00:43:03,200 --> 00:43:10,720
larger and larger, moving a greater distance per 
candle. This shows a gain in bullish momentum.  

409
00:43:10,720 --> 00:43:17,840
In a downtrend, each candle gets larger and 
larger, moving a greater distance per candle,  

410
00:43:17,840 --> 00:43:24,640
indicating a gain in bearish momentum. When 
you see consecutive candles increasing in size,  

411
00:43:24,640 --> 00:43:31,120
it's a clear signal that the trend is gaining 
momentum in that direction. In an uptrend,  

412
00:43:31,120 --> 00:43:37,680
it means buyers are in full control and there 
aren't enough sellers to cause wide swings in  

413
00:43:37,680 --> 00:43:44,720
the opposite direction. In a downtrend, growing 
candles show sellers are dominating the market,  

414
00:43:44,720 --> 00:43:48,720
and there aren't enough buyers 
to counter their pressure.

415
00:43:48,720 --> 00:43:54,240
An Inside Bar is characterized by a bar 
that neither takes out the high nor the  

416
00:43:54,240 --> 00:44:00,640
low of its predecessor. An inside bar is 
easily recognizable due to its relatively  

417
00:44:00,640 --> 00:44:07,280
small spread. The inside bar signifies a loss 
of momentum and uncertainty in the market.  

418
00:44:07,280 --> 00:44:14,560
The smaller candle suggests consolidation after a 
larger move as neither buyers nor sellers are able  

419
00:44:14,560 --> 00:44:21,280
to push the price beyond the previous bar's range. 
The inside bar is also hinting at a potential  

420
00:44:21,280 --> 00:44:28,000
breakout in either direction. When an inside 
bar forms at a crucial spot, such as a major  

421
00:44:28,000 --> 00:44:35,360
support or resistance, its break can trigger 
quite a few traders in and out of position.

422
00:44:35,360 --> 00:44:41,360
When you see several candles in a row failing to 
break through a specific price level, each forming  

423
00:44:41,360 --> 00:44:47,920
long wicks in the same direction, you're looking 
at a Multiple Candle Rejection. In an uptrend,  

424
00:44:47,920 --> 00:44:55,360
if multiple candles try to push above a resistance 
level but fail each time, closing with long upper  

425
00:44:55,360 --> 00:45:03,200
wicks, it's a clear sign of rejection at that 
level. These wicks form a selling pressure zone.  

426
00:45:03,200 --> 00:45:09,440
Multiple candle rejections show the repeated 
failure of price to breach a key level,  

427
00:45:09,440 --> 00:45:16,320
suggesting a strong buying or selling presence 
at that point. When buyers try to push prices  

428
00:45:16,320 --> 00:45:22,960
higher but fail multiple times, it indicates 
that sellers are stepping in aggressively to  

429
00:45:22,960 --> 00:45:30,000
defend that level. The long upper wicks represent 
the failed attempts of buyers to gain control.  

430
00:45:30,000 --> 00:45:36,320
Similarly, when sellers try to drive prices 
lower but encounter repeated rejection,  

431
00:45:36,320 --> 00:45:42,240
it suggests strong buying interest at 
that level. The long lower wicks signal  

432
00:45:42,240 --> 00:45:49,520
the inability of sellers to close below that 
price. These wicks form a buying pressure zone.

433
00:45:49,520 --> 00:45:56,640
As price approaches a key level, you'll notice the 
candles getting smaller in size. Their spread gets  

434
00:45:56,640 --> 00:46:02,960
lower and lower. This pattern of successive 
candles shrinking in size is a clear sign of  

435
00:46:02,960 --> 00:46:10,320
Decreasing Candles. Decreasing candles indicate 
a loss of momentum as prices approach a critical  

436
00:46:10,320 --> 00:46:16,880
point in the market. The smaller candles suggest 
that the distance traveled per candle is getting  

437
00:46:16,880 --> 00:46:23,280
shorter, which is an early signal that the 
current trend is losing steam. For example,  

438
00:46:23,280 --> 00:46:28,480
in an uptrend approaching resistance, 
decreasing candles show that buyers  

439
00:46:28,480 --> 00:46:35,760
are losing control and momentum. In a downtrend 
nearing support, decreasing candles reveal that  

440
00:46:35,760 --> 00:46:42,000
sellers are losing their grip on the market. 
To increase the quality of your trade setup,  

441
00:46:42,000 --> 00:46:48,880
look for decreasing candles that finish with 
multiple long wick candles at the key level.  

442
00:46:48,880 --> 00:46:53,280
This combination suggests 
a strong loss of momentum.

443
00:46:53,280 --> 00:46:59,760
With this method, you'll soon realize that reading 
price action isn't about memorizing dozens of  

444
00:46:59,760 --> 00:47:05,680
candlesticks. It's about observing price bars 
as they form and understanding what the market  

445
00:47:05,680 --> 00:47:12,800
has done and is currently doing. The context of 
the price move is crucial. A candle can have a  

446
00:47:12,800 --> 00:47:18,800
completely different meaning depending on where it 
appears in a price trend. Is it at the beginning,  

447
00:47:18,800 --> 00:47:25,360
middle, or end of a trend? Is it at a support or 
resistance or in the middle of a consolidation  

448
00:47:25,360 --> 00:47:34,160
phase? Always analyze candlesticks in the context 
of the overall price move, never in isolation.

449
00:47:34,160 --> 00:47:39,840
Now, let's talk a bit about pullbacks. 
A pullback is a temporary price movement  

450
00:47:39,840 --> 00:47:46,160
that goes against the prevailing trend. It's 
a period of price retracement or correction  

451
00:47:46,160 --> 00:47:51,360
before the trend resumes its original 
direction. Pullbacks occur when price  

452
00:47:51,360 --> 00:47:57,440
moves in the opposite direction of the trend 
for at least one bar. The psychology behind  

453
00:47:57,440 --> 00:48:03,280
pullbacks involves a temporary shift 
in market sentiment. During an uptrend,  

454
00:48:03,280 --> 00:48:10,640
a pullback occurs when bearish pressure briefly 
overcomes bullish pressure, driving prices lower.  

455
00:48:10,640 --> 00:48:16,480
However, this doesn't necessarily indicate a 
trend reversal. If the lower prices fail to  

456
00:48:16,480 --> 00:48:22,080
attract enough selling pressure to break the 
previous swing low, it suggests the pullback  

457
00:48:22,080 --> 00:48:28,800
is merely a correction within the larger 
uptrend. As sentiment shifts back to bullish,  

458
00:48:28,800 --> 00:48:35,920
more buying enters the market. Shorts will cover 
their positions and the uptrend will resume.

459
00:48:35,920 --> 00:48:40,640
Now, not all pullbacks are created 
equal. We can classify them into  

460
00:48:40,640 --> 00:48:46,720
two main types based on their depth: 
Shallow Pullbacks and Deep Pullbacks.

461
00:48:46,720 --> 00:48:53,440
Shallow pullbacks are corrections that 
retrace only about 25% to 30% of the  

462
00:48:53,440 --> 00:48:58,560
current leg of the trend. They indicate 
that the trend is still quite strong as  

463
00:48:58,560 --> 00:49:05,120
the counter-trend moves are relatively minor. 
However, because the pullbacks are so shallow,  

464
00:49:05,120 --> 00:49:10,960
it can be tricky to time your entries 
and define your risk when trading these.

465
00:49:10,960 --> 00:49:17,920
Deep pullbacks are corrections that retrace 
roughly 50% or more of the current trend leg.  

466
00:49:17,920 --> 00:49:22,800
These are often viewed as more favorable 
trading opportunities as they allow you to  

467
00:49:22,800 --> 00:49:29,200
get into the trend at a better price with 
a more attractive risk-to-reward ratio.  

468
00:49:29,200 --> 00:49:34,240
One of the main benefits of trading pullbacks 
is the potential for higher probability  

469
00:49:34,240 --> 00:49:40,320
entries. When a strong price action signal 
occurs at a key level following a pullback,  

470
00:49:40,320 --> 00:49:45,760
it indicates a high likelihood of the trend 
continuing. Confirmation is key when trading  

471
00:49:45,760 --> 00:49:50,720
pullbacks. Look for candlestick patterns 
to confirm the pullback is ending and the  

472
00:49:50,720 --> 00:49:56,800
trend is likely to resume. In an uptrend, the more 
subdued the bearish pressure during the pullback,  

473
00:49:56,800 --> 00:50:01,600
the higher the odds of a successful 
trend continuation. If done correctly,  

474
00:50:01,600 --> 00:50:08,960
trading pullbacks will allow you to buy low 
in uptrends and sell high in downtrends.

475
00:50:08,960 --> 00:50:14,720
When it comes to breakouts and false breakouts, 
you need to understand how to distinguish between  

476
00:50:14,720 --> 00:50:21,760
the two. A true breakout can lead to a powerful 
new trend, while a false breakout can trap traders  

477
00:50:21,760 --> 00:50:28,640
on the wrong side of the market. One key thing to 
watch for is how price behaves after breaking out  

478
00:50:28,640 --> 00:50:34,640
of a trading range. If it quickly reverses and 
comes back into the range, that's a sign of a  

479
00:50:34,640 --> 00:50:41,600
potential false breakout. Often these false moves 
are engineered by large institutional traders to  

480
00:50:41,600 --> 00:50:47,680
build liquidity before driving the market in the 
opposite direction. To avoid getting caught in  

481
00:50:47,680 --> 00:50:54,640
these traps, it's wise to wait for a retest of the 
breakout level before entering a trade. Look for  

482
00:50:54,640 --> 00:51:01,120
price to hold outside the breakout level on the 
retest. In a true breakout, price should continue  

483
00:51:01,120 --> 00:51:09,120
in the breakout direction, making new highs or 
lows. However, if the breakout fails and price  

484
00:51:09,120 --> 00:51:16,080
remains stuck in a larger trading range, that's a 
sign that the attempted trend change has failed.

485
00:51:16,080 --> 00:51:22,480
Another thing to consider is the overall market 
context. In a bull market, upward breakouts tend  

486
00:51:22,480 --> 00:51:30,000
to be more reliable and profitable, while bear 
markets favor downward breakouts. Trading with a  

487
00:51:30,000 --> 00:51:36,480
prevailing trend will tilt the odds in your favor. 
Remember, the market doesn't have to respect the  

488
00:51:36,480 --> 00:51:43,840
levels we draw on our charts. False breakouts 
will occur with varying degrees of aggression.

489
00:51:43,840 --> 00:51:48,480
There are two main types of patterns that 
every price action trader should know:  

490
00:51:48,480 --> 00:51:52,080
Reversal Patterns and Continuation Patterns.

491
00:51:52,080 --> 00:51:58,160
Reversal patterns signal that the current trend 
may be coming to an end and the price could change  

492
00:51:58,160 --> 00:52:04,560
direction. The Head and Shoulders is the most 
popular reversal pattern. It often signals that  

493
00:52:04,560 --> 00:52:11,520
an uptrend is about to reverse into a downtrend. 
The opposite is an Inverted Head and Shoulders,  

494
00:52:11,520 --> 00:52:18,000
which can form at the bottom of a downtrend, 
hinting at a potential bullish reversal. Double  

495
00:52:18,000 --> 00:52:24,240
Tops and Double Bottoms should be your main focal 
point. These form when price tests the level twice  

496
00:52:24,240 --> 00:52:30,560
but can't break through, suggesting the trend 
is losing momentum. A double top often leads  

497
00:52:30,560 --> 00:52:37,600
to a bearish reversal, while a double bottom 
can result in a bullish reversal. Triple Tops  

498
00:52:37,600 --> 00:52:44,080
and Triple Bottoms are similar, with the price 
testing a level three times before reversing.

499
00:52:44,080 --> 00:52:49,840
Continuation patterns suggest that the current 
trend is just taking a breather before likely  

500
00:52:49,840 --> 00:52:56,240
resuming. Flags and Pennants form quite 
often. These appear as brief consolidations  

501
00:52:56,240 --> 00:53:01,680
or pullbacks against the prevailing trend. 
They usually lead to the trend continuing  

502
00:53:01,680 --> 00:53:08,240
once price breaks out of the pattern in the 
direction of the prior trend. Triangles are  

503
00:53:08,240 --> 00:53:14,080
usually continuation patterns with the trend 
expected to resume in the direction it was going  

504
00:53:14,080 --> 00:53:19,760
before the triangle formed. Rectangles 
are my favorite continuation patterns.  

505
00:53:19,760 --> 00:53:26,320
These are sideways channels where price bounces 
between support and resistance. I like to trade  

506
00:53:26,320 --> 00:53:32,640
false breakouts that occur contrary to the 
prevailing trend. So in an uptrend, look  

507
00:53:32,640 --> 00:53:41,280
to trade false breakouts below support. And in a 
downtrend, trade false breakouts above resistance.

508
00:53:41,280 --> 00:53:45,760
While knowing these classic patterns is 
important, you need to look at them through  

509
00:53:45,760 --> 00:53:52,000
the lens of price action. Simply memorizing 
patterns is not enough. You must understand  

510
00:53:52,000 --> 00:53:57,840
the market dynamics and psychology behind 
them. This means paying close attention to  

511
00:53:57,840 --> 00:54:04,960
market structure and the key levels on the chart. 
Look for price zones where the market has changed  

512
00:54:04,960 --> 00:54:11,280
direction multiple times before. If a chart 
pattern forms near one of these key levels,  

513
00:54:11,280 --> 00:54:17,280
it can add significance to the pattern 
signal. The overall trend is also crucial.  

514
00:54:17,280 --> 00:54:23,120
"Trend is your friend," as they say. In 
an uptrend, bullish continuation patterns  

515
00:54:23,120 --> 00:54:29,440
are more likely to succeed. In a downtrend, 
bearish continuation patterns have a higher  

516
00:54:29,440 --> 00:54:35,520
probability. You always want to trade in the 
direction of the path of least resistance.

517
00:54:35,520 --> 00:54:41,200
When a reversal pattern forms, it's signaling 
that the trend may be in trouble, but it's not  

518
00:54:41,200 --> 00:54:48,240
a guarantee. Often times reversal patterns 
will fail and the prior trend will resume.  

519
00:54:48,240 --> 00:54:54,480
Don't jump in on the first sign of a reversal. 
Wait for price to confirm it. During pullbacks  

520
00:54:54,480 --> 00:55:00,000
or retracements against the main trend, 
continuation patterns can offer low-risk  

521
00:55:00,000 --> 00:55:07,200
entries. If you expect the trend to resume again, 
look for fake-outs against the current trend.  

522
00:55:07,200 --> 00:55:14,000
When a pattern breakout fails and price quickly 
reverses, these are good opportunities to enter,  

523
00:55:14,000 --> 00:55:19,360
capitalizing on trapped traders who 
thought the trend was about to change.

524
00:55:19,360 --> 00:55:25,760
No two patterns are exactly alike in the real 
world. As you analyze more and more charts,  

525
00:55:25,760 --> 00:55:32,160
you'll develop a keener eye for the subtleties 
that separate successful patterns from failures.  

526
00:55:32,160 --> 00:55:36,880
You'll start to recognize how certain 
patterns tend to play out in specific  

527
00:55:36,880 --> 00:55:42,960
markets, timeframes, or conditions. 
Of course, no pattern is guaranteed.  

528
00:55:42,960 --> 00:55:48,960
Approach patterns with the combination 
of respect and skepticism they deserve.

529
00:55:48,960 --> 00:55:55,600
Price action becomes 10 times more effective with 
the help of volume. Volume is the lifeblood of the  

530
00:55:55,600 --> 00:56:01,920
markets. It reflects the actual buying and selling 
pressure behind every price move. When you're  

531
00:56:01,920 --> 00:56:08,320
looking at a chart, the price bars show you what's 
happening, but the volume bars reveal why it's  

532
00:56:08,320 --> 00:56:15,840
happening. Volume tells you about the intensity, 
urgency, and commitment behind the price action.

533
00:56:15,840 --> 00:56:22,320
Here's how you can use volume to confirm or 
question what you're seeing in the price. First,  

534
00:56:22,320 --> 00:56:29,200
look for convergence between volume and price. In 
an uptrend, rising prices should be accompanied by  

535
00:56:29,200 --> 00:56:37,200
rising volume. This shows genuine buying interest 
that can sustain the move. In a downtrend, falling  

536
00:56:37,200 --> 00:56:44,000
prices with increasing volume signals strong 
selling pressure that could drive prices lower.

537
00:56:44,000 --> 00:56:49,760
Be wary of divergences. If prices 
are rising but volume is falling,  

538
00:56:49,760 --> 00:56:57,040
it's a warning sign. The uptrend may be losing 
steam. Buyers are less committed. An upside  

539
00:56:57,040 --> 00:57:05,040
breakout on low volume is suspect. Likewise, 
if prices are falling but volume is drying up,  

540
00:57:05,040 --> 00:57:10,720
sellers may be losing control. The 
downtrend could be nearing exhaustion.

541
00:57:10,720 --> 00:57:16,160
Look for volume spikes near support and 
resistance. Major players often show  

542
00:57:16,160 --> 00:57:23,360
their hand at key levels. If there's a volume 
surge as price tests a support level and holds,  

543
00:57:23,360 --> 00:57:27,840
that's often a sign of strong demand 
absorbing the selling pressure;  

544
00:57:27,840 --> 00:57:35,200
the support is likely to hold. Also track 
volume during breakouts. A valid breakout  

545
00:57:35,200 --> 00:57:42,080
(up or down) should occur with an expansion 
in volume. This confirms the price action.  

546
00:57:42,080 --> 00:57:49,360
But a breakout on low volume is more likely to 
fail, trapping traders in the wrong direction.

547
00:57:49,360 --> 00:57:56,240
Also, watch for Climactic Volume. After a strong 
run-up, a huge volume spike with a wide range  

548
00:57:56,240 --> 00:58:03,120
price bar can signal buying exhaustion—a 
Buying Climax. Supply may be taking over.  

549
00:58:03,120 --> 00:58:11,200
The uptrend is in jeopardy. The reverse is true 
for a Selling Climax after an extended decline.

550
00:58:11,200 --> 00:58:18,400
Monitor the volume patterns in consolidations. 
Is volume contracting as the price range narrows?  

551
00:58:18,400 --> 00:58:25,280
This can be a sign of decreasing volatility 
and building pressure for the next move. Also,  

552
00:58:25,280 --> 00:58:32,320
look for high volume reversal bars. A wide range 
bar on massive volume that reverses an existing  

553
00:58:32,320 --> 00:58:40,240
trend is a red flag. For example, a bearish 
momentum bar with huge volume after an uptrend  

554
00:58:40,240 --> 00:58:47,760
is a sign that sellers have taken control. Think 
of volume as the fuel and price as the vehicle.  

555
00:58:47,760 --> 00:58:54,480
A rally or decline can only go as far as the fuel 
in the tank. As a price action trader, you always  

556
00:58:54,480 --> 00:59:01,600
want to be on the stronger side of the market—the 
side with more aggressive volume behind it.

557
00:59:01,600 --> 00:59:08,400
Market prices move based on the flow of buy and 
sell orders. More buying pressure pushes prices  

558
00:59:08,400 --> 00:59:15,280
up while more selling pressure pushes prices 
down. For substantial price movements to occur,  

559
00:59:15,280 --> 00:59:22,720
the market needs to interact with areas of high 
order concentration, also known as liquidity. So,  

560
00:59:22,720 --> 00:59:28,960
liquidity means all the buy and sell orders 
waiting to be filled. Now, here's the interesting  

561
00:59:28,960 --> 00:59:36,080
part. If there isn't enough liquidity, the big 
players (the Smart Money) will create it. For big  

562
00:59:36,080 --> 00:59:42,480
traders like banks or hedge funds, liquidity 
is critical. They deal with large amounts of  

563
00:59:42,480 --> 00:59:49,120
money. In less liquid markets, their big trades 
can push prices around a lot. This makes it hard  

564
00:59:49,120 --> 00:59:55,520
for them to buy or sell without losing money. 
Now, if you understand where liquidity sits,  

565
00:59:55,520 --> 01:00:02,080
you can identify Magnet Areas—those 
price levels that attract price movement.

566
01:00:02,080 --> 01:00:07,680
Your main task is to find Liquidity 
Pools. Liquidity pools are like busy  

567
01:00:07,680 --> 01:00:13,760
trading spots in the market. They're areas 
where lots of buy and sell orders gather,  

568
01:00:13,760 --> 01:00:19,200
and they form at key price levels. 
These could be previous highs or lows,  

569
01:00:19,200 --> 01:00:25,040
round numbers, or other important points. 
We'll talk about these in a minute. Now,  

570
01:00:25,040 --> 01:00:32,080
traders often place their orders at these 
levels creating a cluster of potential trades.

571
01:00:32,080 --> 01:00:35,280
There are different types of liquidity pools:

572
01:00:35,280 --> 01:00:41,920
Major Liquidity Pools: These form at the highs 
and lows of longer timeframes. These are big,  

573
01:00:41,920 --> 01:00:45,440
important levels that many 
traders watch. You might see  

574
01:00:45,440 --> 01:00:52,400
them on weekly, monthly, or even yearly charts.
Medium Liquidity Pools: These show up on shorter  

575
01:00:52,400 --> 01:01:00,160
timeframes like 1-hour charts. These are still 
significant but not as big as the major pools. 

576
01:01:00,160 --> 01:01:06,000
Minor Liquidity Pools: These appear on 
very short timeframes like 1-minute or  

577
01:01:06,000 --> 01:01:12,800
5-minute charts. These are smaller and might 
only matter for very short-term traders. 

578
01:01:12,800 --> 01:01:18,400
Liquidity pools work by attracting price. 
When price approaches a liquidity pool,  

579
01:01:18,400 --> 01:01:25,840
a few things can happen. It might reverse as 
lots of orders get filled at that level, or it  

580
01:01:25,840 --> 01:01:32,640
might pause there before continuing. Sometimes it 
might even break through quickly if there's enough  

581
01:01:32,640 --> 01:01:40,160
momentum. And big players are constantly trying to 
hunt these liquidity pools. They often push price  

582
01:01:40,160 --> 01:01:47,440
to these levels to trigger a bunch of orders, 
causing a sharp move. So, liquidity zones are  

583
01:01:47,440 --> 01:01:53,920
key areas where Smart Money players often target 
to protect their positions and to trap other  

584
01:01:53,920 --> 01:02:02,000
traders. These zones act like magnets for price, 
drawing it in and often causing significant moves.

585
01:02:02,000 --> 01:02:09,280
So, let's talk about each type of liquidity zone 
and how Smart Money uses them to their advantage.

586
01:02:09,280 --> 01:02:16,640
First area is around Structural Highs and Lows. 
These are major turning points in price action—the  

587
01:02:16,640 --> 01:02:22,960
peaks and valleys you see on a chart that stand 
out from the rest. Smart Money loves these  

588
01:02:22,960 --> 01:02:30,320
spots because they know traders often place their 
stop-losses just beyond them. Let's say we have a  

589
01:02:30,320 --> 01:02:38,320
strong uptrend with a series of higher highs and 
higher lows. Traders often jump on this trend,  

590
01:02:38,320 --> 01:02:45,120
placing their stops just below the most recent 
low. And Smart Money knows this. They often push  

591
01:02:45,120 --> 01:02:52,960
the price down, breaking that low and triggering 
all those stop-losses. This flood of sell orders  

592
01:02:52,960 --> 01:03:00,400
drives the price down further, often before Smart 
Money steps in to buy at a discount. The same  

593
01:03:00,400 --> 01:03:07,520
happens in downtrends. Retail shorts place their 
stops above recent highs. Smart Money spike the  

594
01:03:07,520 --> 01:03:14,640
price up, hit those stops, then drive the price 
back down. To spot these zones, look for clear  

595
01:03:14,640 --> 01:03:21,840
swing highs and lows. The more obvious they are, 
the more likely they are to attract attention.

596
01:03:21,840 --> 01:03:28,400
Trend Lines are another favorite tool of traders. 
The diagonal lines that connect a series of lows  

597
01:03:28,400 --> 01:03:35,920
in an uptrend or highs in a downtrend. They 
are simple to draw and easy to understand,  

598
01:03:35,920 --> 01:03:43,280
which is why so many traders rely on them. Big 
players often target these trend lines, especially  

599
01:03:43,280 --> 01:03:50,320
long-standing ones. They know that many traders 
will have stop-losses placed just beyond these  

600
01:03:50,320 --> 01:03:57,840
lines. By breaking a significant trend line, they 
can trigger a cascade of orders. For instance,  

601
01:03:57,840 --> 01:04:05,120
in a long-standing uptrend, many traders will be 
long with their stops just below the trend line.  

602
01:04:05,120 --> 01:04:11,840
Smart Money might push the price down to break 
this line. As stops are hit, more sell orders  

603
01:04:11,840 --> 01:04:19,840
flood in. Smart Money can then step in and buy 
at lower prices before resuming the uptrend.

604
01:04:19,840 --> 01:04:26,960
Equal Highs and Lows, also known as Double Tops 
and Double Bottoms, are also exploited by Smart  

605
01:04:26,960 --> 01:04:34,080
Money. These patterns form when price reaches the 
same level twice, creating a potential reversal  

606
01:04:34,080 --> 01:04:41,920
point. Traders often see these patterns and 
place their trades accordingly. For a double top,  

607
01:04:41,920 --> 01:04:47,760
they might go short with a stop just above 
the equal highs. For a double bottom,  

608
01:04:47,760 --> 01:04:54,800
they might go long with a stop just below the 
equal lows. Smart Money knows this and often  

609
01:04:54,800 --> 01:05:01,200
pushes the price just beyond these levels 
to trigger stop-losses before reversing.  

610
01:05:01,200 --> 01:05:06,160
This creates a liquidity pool that 
they can use to their advantage.

611
01:05:06,160 --> 01:05:12,800
Trading Sessions, particularly the Asian, London, 
and New York sessions, often create their own  

612
01:05:12,800 --> 01:05:19,120
ranges. These ranges can become significant 
liquidity zones, especially at their highs and  

613
01:05:19,120 --> 01:05:25,840
lows. Big players often target the session's 
highs because they know many traders use them  

614
01:05:25,840 --> 01:05:33,440
for entries and stop placements. For example, 
many traders use the Asian session range as a  

615
01:05:33,440 --> 01:05:40,960
guide for the London session. They might place buy 
orders above the Asian high and sell orders below  

616
01:05:40,960 --> 01:05:48,400
the Asian low. Smart Money might push the price 
just beyond these levels to trigger these orders,  

617
01:05:48,400 --> 01:05:54,400
creating liquidity that they can trade against. 
They might spike the price above the Asian high,  

618
01:05:54,400 --> 01:06:01,760
triggering buy orders, only to sell into 
this liquidity and push the price back down.

619
01:06:01,760 --> 01:06:07,920
The Previous Day's High and Low are other 
significant levels that many traders watch.  

620
01:06:07,920 --> 01:06:14,000
They often serve as support and resistance 
levels for the current day's trading. Again,  

621
01:06:14,000 --> 01:06:20,880
the big boys frequently target these levels. 
For instance, many traders place buy orders  

622
01:06:20,880 --> 01:06:27,040
just above the previous day's high, expecting 
the upward momentum to continue. Smart Money  

623
01:06:27,040 --> 01:06:32,880
will push the price up to trigger these 
orders, creating a pool of liquidity.  

624
01:06:32,880 --> 01:06:39,040
They can then sell into this liquidity, 
potentially reversing the price direction.

625
01:06:39,040 --> 01:06:45,200
The Previous Week's High and Low also attract a 
lot of attention. You might not even know where  

626
01:06:45,200 --> 01:06:52,560
those levels are. These levels often act as key 
support and resistance on higher timeframes,  

627
01:06:52,560 --> 01:06:59,680
and Smart Money often exploit these levels knowing 
that many swing traders and position traders use  

628
01:06:59,680 --> 01:07:07,120
them for stop placement and entry orders. For 
example, in a downtrend, many traders might  

629
01:07:07,120 --> 01:07:14,160
place sell orders below the previous week's low, 
expecting the trend to continue. Smart Money often  

630
01:07:14,160 --> 01:07:21,520
push the price down to trigger these orders, 
creating a liquidity pool they can buy into.

631
01:07:21,520 --> 01:07:28,800
Supply and Demand Zones are other liquidity zones. 
These are areas where price has shown significant  

632
01:07:28,800 --> 01:07:36,880
rejection in the past, and these zones are prime 
targets for Smart Money manipulation. Smart Money  

633
01:07:36,880 --> 01:07:43,520
know many traders place their orders around 
them. For example, many traders might place  

634
01:07:43,520 --> 01:07:50,640
buy orders at a strong demand zone. Smart Money 
might push the price into this zone, triggering  

635
01:07:50,640 --> 01:07:57,440
these buy orders and creating liquidity. They 
can then potentially sell into this liquidity,  

636
01:07:57,440 --> 01:08:03,680
driving the price even lower. That's why you see 
so many demand zones that should work in theory,  

637
01:08:03,680 --> 01:08:11,120
but in reality, they fail. The same happens with 
supply zones. Traders often place sell orders  

638
01:08:11,120 --> 01:08:18,080
at these levels, expecting price to drop. Smart 
Money might spike the price into the supply zone,  

639
01:08:18,080 --> 01:08:25,920
triggering these sell orders, then buy into this 
liquidity to potentially drive the price higher.

640
01:08:25,920 --> 01:08:33,680
Fair Value Gaps (FVG) are also targeted. These are 
areas on the chart where price has moved rapidly.  

641
01:08:33,680 --> 01:08:41,360
These gaps often act as magnets for price, drawing 
it back to fill the gap. Smart Money often uses  

642
01:08:41,360 --> 01:08:48,960
these gaps as targets. For example, if there's a 
bullish fair value gap below the current price,  

643
01:08:48,960 --> 01:08:56,640
many traders might place buy orders in this area, 
expecting price to come back and fill the gap.  

644
01:08:56,640 --> 01:09:00,480
Smart Money might push the 
price down through this level,  

645
01:09:00,480 --> 01:09:06,320
triggering these buy orders and creating 
liquidity. The same happens with bearish  

646
01:09:06,320 --> 01:09:12,400
fair value gaps above the current price. 
Traders often place sell orders in these  

647
01:09:12,400 --> 01:09:19,440
areas. Smart Money might spike the price up 
through the gap, triggering the sell orders.  

648
01:09:19,440 --> 01:09:25,280
That's why maybe 90% of fair value gaps 
fail, but that's a topic for another video.

649
01:09:26,160 --> 01:09:32,720
Round Numbers ending in zero or double zeros 
are psychologically significant levels that  

650
01:09:32,720 --> 01:09:39,360
attract a lot of attention. These levels are 
prime targets for Smart Money manipulation.  

651
01:09:39,360 --> 01:09:45,040
Smart Money knows that many traders place 
their orders around these round numbers.  

652
01:09:45,040 --> 01:09:51,600
They might place buy orders just above a 
round number or sell orders just below it.  

653
01:09:51,600 --> 01:09:57,760
The big boys often push the price to these levels 
to trigger these orders, creating liquidity that  

654
01:09:57,760 --> 01:10:04,080
they can trade against. For instance, if 
there's a round number at the $50 level,  

655
01:10:04,080 --> 01:10:11,440
many traders might place buy orders slightly above 
it, expecting the price to rise above this level.  

656
01:10:11,440 --> 01:10:18,720
The big boys might push the price up to trigger 
these buy orders, creating a pool of liquidity.  

657
01:10:18,720 --> 01:10:24,320
They can then potentially sell into this 
liquidity, driving the price back down.

658
01:10:24,320 --> 01:10:30,720
Understanding all these liquidity zones and how 
Smart Money targets them is key. It helps you  

659
01:10:30,720 --> 01:10:38,320
avoid common traps. As you practice, you'll start 
to see patterns. You might notice that price often  

660
01:10:38,320 --> 01:10:45,440
reverses after taking out a previous high or 
low. Or you might see that certain levels keep  

661
01:10:45,440 --> 01:10:52,080
causing price to pause or reverse. And please 
don't just draw liquidity zones all over your  

662
01:10:52,080 --> 01:10:59,920
chart. Focus on the most important ones. Too many 
zones can make your analysis confusing. Also,  

663
01:10:59,920 --> 01:11:05,360
pay attention to how price reacts when 
it reaches a liquidity zone. Does it  

664
01:11:05,360 --> 01:11:11,600
reverse sharply? Does it pause and then 
continue? Or does it blow right through?  

665
01:11:11,600 --> 01:11:17,680
This can give you clues about the strength 
of the move and what might happen next. You  

666
01:11:17,680 --> 01:11:23,120
might notice that certain types of zones 
work better in certain market conditions  

667
01:11:23,120 --> 01:11:29,600
or for certain currency pairs or stocks. This 
is where keeping a detailed trading journal  

668
01:11:29,600 --> 01:11:37,120
with your findings can be incredibly valuable, 
allowing you to refine your strategy over time.

669
01:11:37,120 --> 01:11:40,240
Now, let's talk about Liquidity Inducement.  

670
01:11:40,240 --> 01:11:46,320
Inducement is about creating situations that 
make other traders want to trade at certain  

671
01:11:46,320 --> 01:11:52,240
levels. This creates available liquidity 
for bigger players to use when they want to  

672
01:11:52,240 --> 01:11:58,640
enter or exit their positions. To understand 
this better, let's look at how the market is  

673
01:11:58,640 --> 01:12:05,040
structured. When we look at charts, we 
see highs and lows. Above these highs,  

674
01:12:05,040 --> 01:12:12,480
we assume there's buy-side liquidity, and below 
the lows, we assume there's sell-side liquidity.

675
01:12:12,480 --> 01:12:18,960
Buy-Side Liquidity is all the liquidity that 
buyers will use, created mainly by stop-loss  

676
01:12:18,960 --> 01:12:26,880
orders of sellers and buy-stop orders of buyers. 
In a bullish market, price often uses buy-side  

677
01:12:26,880 --> 01:12:34,240
liquidity to fuel the next upward move. To have a 
big bullish move, the market needs sell orders to  

678
01:12:34,240 --> 01:12:41,920
generate more liquidity. Also, the buy orders from 
stop-losses of sellers generate more buy orders,  

679
01:12:41,920 --> 01:12:47,120
which is why you often see a surge 
in buying when price breaks out.

680
01:12:47,120 --> 01:12:52,240
Sell-Side Liquidity is the opposite. 
It's the liquidity that sellers will use,  

681
01:12:52,240 --> 01:12:58,320
created mainly by stop-loss orders of 
buyers and sell-stop orders of sellers.

682
01:12:58,320 --> 01:13:04,480
Imagine you see a double bottom on your 
chart. Price hits the same low point twice,  

683
01:13:04,480 --> 01:13:11,040
forming a support level. Many traders might 
want to buy at this support level. Now,  

684
01:13:11,040 --> 01:13:16,400
think about where these traders would put 
their stop-losses. They'd likely put them  

685
01:13:16,400 --> 01:13:22,800
just below the lows. This creates a pool 
of sell-side liquidity below the lows.  

686
01:13:22,800 --> 01:13:28,800
This is important because big players need this 
liquidity. They can't just jump into the market  

687
01:13:28,800 --> 01:13:35,920
with huge orders. That would cause wild price 
swings and could work against them. Instead,  

688
01:13:35,920 --> 01:13:42,800
they use liquidity inducement to their advantage. 
These big players create patterns or situations  

689
01:13:42,800 --> 01:13:49,840
in the market that encourage other traders to 
place their orders in predictable spots. This  

690
01:13:49,840 --> 01:13:57,280
builds up pools of liquidity that the big players 
can then use to enter or exit their positions.

691
01:13:57,280 --> 01:14:01,920
Now, before we continue, let us know 
in the comments what topics you'd like  

692
01:14:01,920 --> 01:14:08,240
us to cover and please drop us a like 
to help us with the YouTube algorithm.

693
01:14:08,240 --> 01:14:13,680
Now, let's talk about how big players 
use this liquidity. They often create  

694
01:14:13,680 --> 01:14:20,000
what's called a Liquidity Sweep. It's when big 
players in the market try to take advantage of  

695
01:14:20,000 --> 01:14:26,320
areas where there's a lot of buy or sell 
orders waiting. These areas are like pools  

696
01:14:26,320 --> 01:14:32,480
of money just sitting there ready to be used. 
For instance, if there's a strong support level  

697
01:14:32,480 --> 01:14:38,400
with many stop-losses just below it, price 
might sweep down to hit those stops before  

698
01:14:38,400 --> 01:14:45,120
reversing. This action sweeps the liquidity, 
letting larger players fill their orders.

699
01:14:45,840 --> 01:14:52,320
Knowing about liquidity sweeps can help you in two 
main ways. First, you can look for where sweeps  

700
01:14:52,320 --> 01:14:59,520
have already happened as this might show where 
big players have been active. Second, you can use  

701
01:14:59,520 --> 01:15:06,240
this knowledge to guess future moves by spotting 
where available liquidity might be. One way to  

702
01:15:06,240 --> 01:15:13,600
trade these liquidity sweeps is by identifying the 
inducement before a potential zone of interest.  

703
01:15:13,600 --> 01:15:20,400
This is where price action might encourage traders 
to enter positions, creating more liquidity for a  

704
01:15:20,400 --> 01:15:27,520
potential move. For example, if you're looking at 
a possible buy zone, you might see price dip below  

705
01:15:27,520 --> 01:15:34,560
a previous low before the main move up. This 
dip could make sellers enter short positions  

706
01:15:34,560 --> 01:15:42,720
or exit longs, creating liquidity that larger 
players can use to enter their long positions.

707
01:15:42,720 --> 01:15:48,960
Liquidity goes hand-in-hand with the market 
structure. Market structure refers to the  

708
01:15:48,960 --> 01:15:54,720
overall pattern of price movement. It's 
about identifying trends, key levels,  

709
01:15:54,720 --> 01:16:02,000
and the flow of the market. Liquidity is about 
where buying and selling activity clusters.  

710
01:16:02,000 --> 01:16:07,600
These two concepts work together to shape 
market behavior. Here's how they interact:

711
01:16:07,600 --> 01:16:12,960
Areas of high liquidity often become key 
points in the market structure. A level with  

712
01:16:12,960 --> 01:16:19,920
lots of buy orders might become a strong support 
level. If price keeps bouncing off this level,  

713
01:16:19,920 --> 01:16:25,920
it becomes part of the market structure.
Key structural levels tend to attract liquidity.  

714
01:16:26,560 --> 01:16:33,280
Traders often place their orders around important 
structural points like trend lines or previous  

715
01:16:33,280 --> 01:16:40,960
highs and lows. This creates a feedback loop where 
structure and liquidity reinforce each other. 

716
01:16:40,960 --> 01:16:47,200
Breaks in structure can drain liquidity. When 
price breaks through a key structural level,  

717
01:16:47,200 --> 01:16:53,760
it often leads to a surge in trading activity. 
This can temporarily drain liquidity from other  

718
01:16:53,760 --> 01:17:02,400
areas as traders rush to adjust their positions.
Liquidity flows with structure. In a strong trend,  

719
01:17:02,400 --> 01:17:08,880
liquidity tends to cluster in the direction 
of the trend. For example, in an uptrend,  

720
01:17:08,880 --> 01:17:15,520
you might see more liquidity above the current 
price as traders anticipate further rises. 

721
01:17:16,080 --> 01:17:22,480
Structure helps predict liquidity. By reading 
the market structure, you can often predict where  

722
01:17:22,480 --> 01:17:29,760
liquidity might be. For instance, after a series 
of higher lows in an uptrend, you can expect  

723
01:17:29,760 --> 01:17:37,360
liquidity to gather below each of these lows.
Liquidity confirms structure. Sometimes the way  

724
01:17:37,360 --> 01:17:42,240
price interacts with liquidity can 
confirm or deny the current market  

725
01:17:42,240 --> 01:17:48,240
structure. If price easily breaks through 
what should be a liquidity-rich level,  

726
01:17:48,240 --> 01:17:55,600
it might signal a change in the overall structure.
Both liquidity and market structure guide price  

727
01:17:55,600 --> 01:18:02,240
movement. Price often moves towards liquidity 
but within the constraints of the larger market  

728
01:18:02,240 --> 01:18:08,960
structure, and institutional activity links 
them. Big players in the market often use  

729
01:18:08,960 --> 01:18:14,720
their understanding of both liquidity 
and structure to plan their trades.  

730
01:18:14,720 --> 01:18:21,040
Both liquidity and market structure change 
over time. Just as market structure evolves,  

731
01:18:21,040 --> 01:18:27,280
so does the distribution of liquidity. What 
was a key liquidity level last week might  

732
01:18:27,280 --> 01:18:34,560
not be as important now. So, keeping track of 
both helps you stay in tune with the market.  

733
01:18:34,560 --> 01:18:40,560
The interplay between liquidity and structure 
can help you spot truly important levels in the  

734
01:18:40,560 --> 01:18:47,920
market. Areas where structural levels align with 
high liquidity are often the most significant.

735
01:18:47,920 --> 01:18:52,560
In trading, we often talk about 
Market Structure Shifts (MSS)—the  

736
01:18:52,560 --> 01:18:59,600
big changes in the overall trend of the market. 
Inducement often plays a role in these shifts.  

737
01:18:59,600 --> 01:19:05,120
For example, before a major trend change, 
you might see price action that looks like  

738
01:19:05,120 --> 01:19:11,280
it's continuing the old trend. This can trick 
traders into entering positions in the direction  

739
01:19:11,280 --> 01:19:18,480
of the old trend, creating liquidity for the 
Smart Money to use when reversing the market.

740
01:19:18,480 --> 01:19:25,360
Liquidity inducement isn't something bad. If you 
can spot it happening, you might find good trading  

741
01:19:25,360 --> 01:19:32,880
signals for entries. Look for areas where there's 
a lot of liquidity. When the market is going up,  

742
01:19:32,880 --> 01:19:39,520
look for buy entries just below recent 
lows. That's where big players often buy,  

743
01:19:39,520 --> 01:19:44,080
scooping up all the sell orders. 
When the market is going down,  

744
01:19:44,080 --> 01:19:52,400
look to sell just above recent highs. That's where 
big players often sell into all the buy orders.  

745
01:19:52,400 --> 01:19:57,440
For exits, think about where other 
traders might have their stop-losses  

746
01:19:57,440 --> 01:20:04,560
or take-profit orders. These create pools of 
liquidity. As price approaches these areas,  

747
01:20:04,560 --> 01:20:11,600
be ready to exit your trade. The price might 
reverse once it hits these liquidity pools.

748
01:20:11,600 --> 01:20:18,480
Every time the market makes a new range, mark the 
high and low. If you're trading in this range,  

749
01:20:18,480 --> 01:20:24,560
you might enter at one end where there's 
internal liquidity and exit at the other  

750
01:20:24,560 --> 01:20:30,960
end where there's external liquidity. 
Also, you want to trade where there's low  

751
01:20:30,960 --> 01:20:37,520
resistance. This means there should be little 
stopping for the price to move in your favor.

752
01:20:37,520 --> 01:20:44,240
Start on a bigger timeframe like the daily 
chart. Mark major liquidity levels. Move  

753
01:20:44,240 --> 01:20:50,640
down to a smaller timeframe like the 1-hour chart. 
Look for price approaching your marked liquidity  

754
01:20:50,640 --> 01:20:57,280
levels. As price gets close to a liquidity 
level, switch to an even smaller timeframe  

755
01:20:57,280 --> 01:21:03,760
like the 15-minute chart. Watch for signs of 
a Stop Hunt—a quick spike through the level  

756
01:21:03,760 --> 01:21:11,280
followed by a reversal. If you see this, get ready 
to enter a trade in the direction of the reversal.  

757
01:21:11,280 --> 01:21:17,280
Also, don't jump on every breakout. Wait for 
the price to show it's really going to keep  

758
01:21:17,280 --> 01:21:24,240
moving in that direction. And always consult 
multiple timeframes. Check larger timeframes  

759
01:21:24,240 --> 01:21:30,000
to see if a move fits the bigger picture 
or if it might be inducement. If you see  

760
01:21:30,000 --> 01:21:36,960
the price quickly reject a level after breaking 
it, be ready for a possible reversal. And don't  

761
01:21:36,960 --> 01:21:43,280
put your stops right at obvious levels. 
That's where inducement often targets.

762
01:21:43,280 --> 01:21:45,920
There are several tools and indicators that can  

763
01:21:45,920 --> 01:21:49,680
help you spot and analyze 
liquidity in the markets.

764
01:21:50,800 --> 01:21:56,800
Volume: This is one of the simplest and 
most effective tools. High volume often  

765
01:21:56,800 --> 01:22:03,840
shows high liquidity. So, look for volume 
spikes which can indicate liquidity events. 

766
01:22:04,720 --> 01:22:10,000
Market Depth Charts: These show pending 
buy and sell orders at different price  

767
01:22:10,000 --> 01:22:15,120
levels. They can help you see where 
liquidity pools might be forming. 

768
01:22:15,920 --> 01:22:22,000
Time and Sales (Tape Reading): This 
shows real-time trades. Large trades  

769
01:22:22,000 --> 01:22:27,120
or clusters of trades at certain 
prices can indicate liquidity. 

770
01:22:27,680 --> 01:22:34,800
Order Flow Indicators: These advanced tools try to 
show the balance of buying and selling pressure. 

771
01:22:35,840 --> 01:22:42,080
Volume Profile: This shows where most trading 
has happened at different price levels,  

772
01:22:42,080 --> 01:22:48,400
helping identify high liquidity zones.
It's best to use a mix of tools and combine  

773
01:22:48,400 --> 01:22:56,000
them with market structure and price action. Also, 
these tools don't directly show liquidity; they  

774
01:22:56,000 --> 01:23:02,960
show things that often relate to liquidity. You 
still need to interpret what they're telling you.

775
01:23:02,960 --> 01:23:08,640
Liquidity and order flow analysis are 
closely linked. Order flow analysis is  

776
01:23:08,640 --> 01:23:13,760
all about understanding the buying and 
selling pressure in the market. This  

777
01:23:13,760 --> 01:23:19,920
pressure often shows up as liquidity. Order 
flow analysis looks at the actual orders  

778
01:23:19,920 --> 01:23:27,280
coming into the market. It tries to spot where 
big players are buying or selling. Basically,  

779
01:23:27,280 --> 01:23:32,160
order flow analysis can help you 
find where liquidity is building up,  

780
01:23:32,160 --> 01:23:39,440
when liquidity is being used up, and potential 
price levels where big players might be active.

781
01:23:39,440 --> 01:23:45,760
In order flow analysis, you need to get 
familiar with several concepts. First one:  

782
01:23:45,760 --> 01:23:53,280
Volume Clusters. Order flow analysis often 
looks for clusters of orders at certain prices.  

783
01:23:53,280 --> 01:24:01,200
These clusters are actually liquidity pools. Next 
concept is Absorption. When a price level absorbs  

784
01:24:01,200 --> 01:24:09,280
a lot of orders without moving much, it's often a 
sign of high liquidity. Here's a familiar concept:  

785
01:24:09,280 --> 01:24:17,360
Imbalances. Order flow tools might show imbalances 
between buy and sell orders. These imbalances can  

786
01:24:17,360 --> 01:24:23,520
create or drain liquidity. It's a lot to talk 
about, but that's a topic for another video.

787
01:24:24,160 --> 01:24:28,560
Retail traders like you and me can 
level the playing field by using  

788
01:24:28,560 --> 01:24:34,240
liquidity analysis to compete with 
institutional traders. Here's how:

789
01:24:34,240 --> 01:24:39,840
Know the closest liquidity pools. Mark 
the areas where lots of buy or sell  

790
01:24:39,840 --> 01:24:47,200
orders cluster. When price hits these spots, 
it often bounces or breaks through fast. You  

791
01:24:47,200 --> 01:24:53,280
need to be ready for both scenarios.
Watch for traps and liquidity sweeps.  

792
01:24:53,280 --> 01:24:58,400
Big players set traps to trick small 
traders. They often push price to key  

793
01:24:58,400 --> 01:25:05,280
levels. Don't fall for these fake-outs.
Use multiple timeframes. Check both  

794
01:25:05,280 --> 01:25:11,120
higher and lower timeframes. This gives you a 
fuller picture of liquidity across different  

795
01:25:11,120 --> 01:25:18,080
market views. It helps you spot potential 
reversals or continuations more accurately. 

796
01:25:18,080 --> 01:25:24,080
Track order flow. Pay attention to how orders 
are coming in. Look for big buy or sell walls  

797
01:25:24,080 --> 01:25:29,920
in the order book. These can signal where 
institutions are placing their orders. 

798
01:25:29,920 --> 01:25:36,080
Identify liquidity gaps. These are areas on 
the chart with little trading activity. Price  

799
01:25:36,080 --> 01:25:41,360
often moves quickly through these zones. 
Knowing where they are can help you set  

800
01:25:41,360 --> 01:25:46,480
better entry and exit points.
Study market structure. Look  

801
01:25:46,480 --> 01:25:52,960
for key swing highs and lows. These 
often mark areas of high liquidity. 

802
01:25:52,960 --> 01:25:58,640
Focus on session overlaps. When major 
trading sessions overlap, liquidity tends  

803
01:25:58,640 --> 01:26:05,737
to increase. This can lead to bigger price 
moves. Use these times to your advantage. 

804
01:26:05,737 --> 01:26:10,640
Don't chase breakouts. Many traders jump 
on breakouts only to get burnt. Instead,  

805
01:26:10,640 --> 01:26:18,560
look for pullbacks to liquidity zones after a 
breakout. This is often where Smart Money enters. 

806
01:26:18,560 --> 01:26:24,320
Use Volume Profile. This tool shows you 
where the most trading has happened at  

807
01:26:24,320 --> 01:26:30,960
different price levels. High volume nodes 
often act as strong liquidity areas. 

808
01:26:30,960 --> 01:26:37,120
The Wyckoff Method is built on three key 
laws that explain how markets work. These  

809
01:26:37,120 --> 01:26:42,640
laws help you see what's really moving 
prices, not just what's on the surface.

810
01:26:42,640 --> 01:26:49,360
Let's start with the Law of Supply and Demand. 
This law is the engine that drives the market.  

811
01:26:49,360 --> 01:26:56,560
It's pretty simple: when more people want to buy 
than sell, prices go up. When more want to sell  

812
01:26:56,560 --> 01:27:03,760
than buy, prices go down. But it's not just about 
numbers of buyers and sellers. It's about how  

813
01:27:03,760 --> 01:27:10,080
much money they're willing to spend. It's about 
the intensity of their actions. One big buyer  

814
01:27:10,080 --> 01:27:17,280
can have more impact than many small sellers. The 
Law of Supply and Demand says that price, volume,  

815
01:27:17,280 --> 01:27:25,120
and trend all work together. Price shows which way 
the market is going. Volume shows how strong that  

816
01:27:25,120 --> 01:27:32,880
move is. When price and volume agree, it confirms 
the market direction. We'll talk about this later.

817
01:27:32,880 --> 01:27:38,480
The Law of Cause and Effect tells us that big 
moves in the market don't just happen out of  

818
01:27:38,480 --> 01:27:44,880
nowhere. They need preparation. It's like a 
rocket launch. Before a rocket can take off,  

819
01:27:44,880 --> 01:27:52,240
it needs a lot of fuel. In the market, that fuel 
is buying or selling pressure building up over  

820
01:27:52,240 --> 01:28:00,000
time. The size of the cause determines the size of 
the effect. A small cause leads to a small move.  

821
01:28:00,000 --> 01:28:07,440
A big cause can lead to a big move. This is why 
Wyckoff traders look for signs of Accumulation  

822
01:28:07,440 --> 01:28:15,680
(buying) or Distribution (selling). These are the 
causes that can lead to big price moves. This law  

823
01:28:15,680 --> 01:28:22,240
helps explain why markets sometimes seem to move 
for no reason. There's always a reason, but it  

824
01:28:22,240 --> 01:28:28,640
might have been building up for a while before you 
noticed it. The Law of Cause and Effect also says  

825
01:28:28,640 --> 01:28:35,520
that if there's no preparation, there will be 
no move. This helps you avoid false signals. If  

826
01:28:35,520 --> 01:28:42,080
you don't see a cause building up, you shouldn't 
expect a big effect. It's all about preparation in  

827
01:28:42,080 --> 01:28:49,520
the market. This often shows up as trading ranges. 
These are periods where price moves sideways,  

828
01:28:49,520 --> 01:28:56,800
bouncing between support and resistance levels. To 
the untrained eye, these might look boring, but to  

829
01:28:56,800 --> 01:29:04,080
a Wyckoff trader, they're exciting. They're where 
the cause is building up for the next big move.

830
01:29:04,080 --> 01:29:10,880
Lastly, we have the Law of Effort versus Result. 
This law helps us spot when something's off in  

831
01:29:10,880 --> 01:29:17,200
the market. It's about comparing the effort 
(usually measured by volume) with the result  

832
01:29:17,200 --> 01:29:23,440
(the price movement). Here's how it works: 
the market is always trying to move one way  

833
01:29:23,440 --> 01:29:30,240
or the other. These attempts can be short 
or long. Either way, they represent effort,  

834
01:29:30,240 --> 01:29:37,520
which we see as volume. If you see a lot of 
volume (meaning effort) but prices barely move  

835
01:29:37,520 --> 01:29:44,560
(meaning result), that's a red flag. It might 
mean the current trend is running out of steam.  

836
01:29:44,560 --> 01:29:51,840
On the flip side, if prices move a lot on 
low volume, that move might not last. This  

837
01:29:51,840 --> 01:29:58,800
law helps you spot divergences. A divergence 
is when the effort and result don't match up.  

838
01:29:58,800 --> 01:30:04,480
It's like a warning sign that something might 
be about to change. The Law of Effort versus  

839
01:30:04,480 --> 01:30:10,240
Result is like a lie detector for the market 
and is especially useful for spotting trend  

840
01:30:10,240 --> 01:30:17,760
changes. Often before a trend changes, you'll see 
a mismatch between effort and result. It's like  

841
01:30:17,760 --> 01:30:24,560
the market is trying hard to keep going in the 
same direction, but it's running out of steam.

842
01:30:24,560 --> 01:30:29,120
The Wyckoff Method breaks down 
market action into four main phases:  

843
01:30:29,120 --> 01:30:34,320
Accumulation, Markup, Distribution, and Markdown.

844
01:30:34,320 --> 01:30:40,480
Accumulation is the first phase. It happens at 
market bottoms. This is when big players start  

845
01:30:40,480 --> 01:30:48,160
buying. They do this quietly so prices don't go 
up too fast. During this phase, prices often move  

846
01:30:48,160 --> 01:30:55,200
sideways. It might look boring, but a lot is 
happening under the surface. In accumulation,  

847
01:30:55,200 --> 01:31:02,240
most people are scared to buy. They think prices 
might keep falling. But Smart Money sees value.  

848
01:31:02,240 --> 01:31:09,200
They buy when others are afraid. This phase can 
last a while. It takes time for big players to buy  

849
01:31:09,200 --> 01:31:15,920
all they want without pushing prices up too 
much. Look for these signs in accumulation:

850
01:31:15,920 --> 01:31:23,200
Prices stop falling and move sideways.
Volume is low but picks up on price dips. 

851
01:31:23,200 --> 01:31:29,120
Price drops don't last long.
Strong buying when prices fall a bit. 

852
01:31:29,120 --> 01:31:33,920
The Uptrend or Markup phase comes 
next. This is when prices start  

853
01:31:33,920 --> 01:31:38,880
to climb. The big players who bought 
during the first phase are now letting  

854
01:31:38,880 --> 01:31:45,040
prices rise. They might even buy more, 
pushing prices higher. In the uptrend,  

855
01:31:45,040 --> 01:31:50,080
more people start to notice the market. 
They see prices going up and want to join  

856
01:31:50,080 --> 01:31:57,680
in. This extra buying helps push prices even 
higher. Look for these signs in an uptrend:

857
01:31:57,680 --> 01:32:04,160
Prices make higher highs and higher lows.
Volume often increases as prices rise. 

858
01:32:04,720 --> 01:32:10,880
Pullbacks are short and shallow.
Each new high is met with strong buying. 

859
01:32:10,880 --> 01:32:17,920
The third phase is Distribution. This happens 
at market tops. Big players who bought low are  

860
01:32:17,920 --> 01:32:24,000
now selling. They sell slowly, just like they 
bought slowly. They don't want to crash the  

861
01:32:24,000 --> 01:32:30,560
market by selling too fast. In distribution, 
most people are excited. They think prices  

862
01:32:30,560 --> 01:32:36,480
will keep going up forever. But Smart Money 
knows better. They are quietly selling to  

863
01:32:36,480 --> 01:32:43,920
these eager buyers. Distribution can also take 
some time. Look for these signs in distribution:

864
01:32:43,920 --> 01:32:51,760
Prices stop rising and move sideways.
Volume might increase, but price rises don't last. 

865
01:32:51,760 --> 01:32:59,120
More volatility with sharp ups and downs.
Each new high is quickly sold into. 

866
01:32:59,120 --> 01:33:05,760
The last phase is the Downtrend or Markdown. 
This is when prices start to fall. The big  

867
01:33:05,760 --> 01:33:12,720
players have finished selling. Now there aren't 
enough buyers to keep prices up. In the downtrend,  

868
01:33:12,720 --> 01:33:20,000
fear takes over. People who bought high start 
to panic and sell. This pushes prices down even  

869
01:33:20,000 --> 01:33:26,880
faster. Like the uptrend, the downtrend often 
moves in waves. Again, look for these signs:

870
01:33:26,880 --> 01:33:31,840
In a downtrend, prices make 
lower lows and lower highs. 

871
01:33:31,840 --> 01:33:37,920
Volume often increases as prices fall.
Bounces are short and weak. 

872
01:33:37,920 --> 01:33:43,760
Each new low is met with more selling.
Most of the money in a trend is made  

873
01:33:43,760 --> 01:33:50,960
in phase two (the uptrend) and phase four (the 
downtrend). The transition phases (Accumulation  

874
01:33:50,960 --> 01:33:57,520
and Distribution) are often trickier to trade. 
They are more about preparing for the next trend.  

875
01:33:57,520 --> 01:34:04,000
One key skill in using the Wyckoff Method 
is identifying Changes in Market Character.  

876
01:34:04,000 --> 01:34:10,400
This is when the market shifts from one phase to 
another. For example, the shift from accumulation  

877
01:34:10,400 --> 01:34:17,200
to uptrend or from distribution to downtrend. 
These changes often happen gradually. The  

878
01:34:17,200 --> 01:34:23,760
market doesn't suddenly switch from one phase 
to another. Instead, it transitions slowly.

879
01:34:23,760 --> 01:34:27,440
Now, let's break down Wyckoff 
Events. They're like clues  

880
01:34:27,440 --> 01:34:31,440
that help us figure out what's 
really going on in the market.

881
01:34:31,440 --> 01:34:37,200
First, we have the Preliminary Support 
(PS). This is when big players start to buy,  

882
01:34:37,200 --> 01:34:43,040
trying to stop prices from falling more. 
It's like putting a floor under the market.  

883
01:34:43,040 --> 01:34:48,080
You might see prices stop dropping 
as fast or even bounce a little.

884
01:34:48,080 --> 01:34:51,040
Next comes the Selling Climax (SC). This is a big  

885
01:34:51,040 --> 01:34:58,320
moment. It's when scared sellers dump their 
positions. Prices often fall hard and fast,  

886
01:34:58,320 --> 01:35:05,200
but the big players are buying during this panic. 
They're getting ready for prices to go up later.

887
01:35:05,200 --> 01:35:11,760
After the selling climax, we see an Automatic 
Rally (AR). Prices bounce up a bit. This happens  

888
01:35:11,760 --> 01:35:19,120
because the selling pressure eases off. It's like 
the market taking a breath after all that selling.

889
01:35:19,120 --> 01:35:22,720
Then we have the Secondary 
Test (ST). Prices fall again,  

890
01:35:22,720 --> 01:35:27,680
but not as low as before. This is 
important. It shows that the big  

891
01:35:27,680 --> 01:35:34,640
drop might be over. Big players are still 
buying, keeping prices from falling too far.

892
01:35:34,640 --> 01:35:40,960
Now we come to the Spring. This is a tricky move. 
Prices dip below the low point of the secondary  

893
01:35:40,960 --> 01:35:47,840
test. It looks like the market might fall more, 
but it's often a fake-out. Prices quickly jump  

894
01:35:47,840 --> 01:35:55,040
back up. This is a key sign that big players are 
done buying and are ready for prices to go up.

895
01:35:55,040 --> 01:36:00,000
After the spring, we see a Sign of 
Strength (SOS). This is a strong move up,  

896
01:36:00,000 --> 01:36:05,760
often with lots of trading. It's like the 
market saying, "We're ready to go up now."

897
01:36:05,760 --> 01:36:11,440
And then we have the Last Point of Support 
(LPS). This is one more dip before the real  

898
01:36:11,440 --> 01:36:17,360
uptrend starts. It's like the market 
taking one last breath before climbing.

899
01:36:17,360 --> 01:36:24,160
These events don't always happen in this exact 
order. Markets are tricky and always changing,  

900
01:36:24,160 --> 01:36:30,160
but knowing these events helps you see the 
big picture. If you see signs of accumulation,  

901
01:36:30,160 --> 01:36:35,040
like the Preliminary Support or Spring, 
it might be a good time to think about  

902
01:36:35,040 --> 01:36:41,680
buying. If you see signs of distribution, 
like a Buying Climax or Sign of Weakness,  

903
01:36:41,680 --> 01:36:48,400
it might be time to be careful or even think 
about selling. The end of an accumulation phase,  

904
01:36:48,400 --> 01:36:55,200
like after a successful Spring, can be a great 
time to buy. The end of a distribution phase  

905
01:36:55,200 --> 01:37:01,680
can be a good time to sell. But remember, you 
don't need to catch the exact bottom or top.  

906
01:37:01,680 --> 01:37:08,240
What matters is catching the main move. And 
don't get too hung up on naming each event.  

907
01:37:08,240 --> 01:37:13,920
What's more important is understanding what these 
events mean. They are showing you the transfer of  

908
01:37:13,920 --> 01:37:20,560
risk in the market. Like I said before, in 
accumulation, Smart Money is taking on risk,  

909
01:37:20,560 --> 01:37:27,280
betting prices will go up. In distribution, 
they are passing that risk to others.

910
01:37:27,280 --> 01:37:33,200
Volume is a key part of the Wyckoff Method. 
It helps confirm what price is telling us.  

911
01:37:33,200 --> 01:37:40,160
The main idea is simple: volume should match 
price moves. If prices go up, volume should  

912
01:37:40,160 --> 01:37:48,320
too. If prices fall, volume should rise. When 
volume and price don't match, it can mean trouble.  

913
01:37:48,320 --> 01:37:55,280
Wyckoff saw the market as a fight between buyers 
and sellers. Volume shows who's winning. High  

914
01:37:55,280 --> 01:38:03,840
volume on up moves means buyers are strong. High 
volume on down moves means sellers are in control.

915
01:38:03,840 --> 01:38:10,800
We talked before about Wyckoff's Law of Effort 
versus Result. This law says the effect of a  

916
01:38:10,800 --> 01:38:17,040
price move should match the effort behind it. 
The effort is shown by volume. The result is  

917
01:38:17,040 --> 01:38:23,600
the price change. Here's how it works: big 
volume (the effort) should lead to big price  

918
01:38:23,600 --> 01:38:30,480
moves (the result). Small volume should lead 
to small price moves. If there's a mismatch,  

919
01:38:30,480 --> 01:38:35,760
it can signal a change coming. High 
volume with little price change often  

920
01:38:35,760 --> 01:38:42,240
means accumulation or distribution. Low 
volume with big price moves usually isn't  

921
01:38:42,240 --> 01:38:49,120
sustainable. Rising prices with falling 
volume can mean the uptrend is weakening.

922
01:38:49,120 --> 01:38:55,360
Volume helps confirm price action. It's like a 
lie detector for price moves. Price alone can  

923
01:38:55,360 --> 01:39:02,000
sometimes lie, but price and volume together 
usually tell the truth. In accumulation,  

924
01:39:02,000 --> 01:39:09,280
watch for high volume on down days that don't 
push prices much lower. This can mean big players  

925
01:39:09,280 --> 01:39:16,880
are buying, soaking up the supply. It's a sign 
the downtrend might be ending. In distribution,  

926
01:39:16,880 --> 01:39:23,200
look for high volume on up days that don't 
push prices much higher. This often means  

927
01:39:23,200 --> 01:39:29,200
big players are selling into strength. 
It's a sign the uptrend might be ending.

928
01:39:29,200 --> 01:39:36,000
During trends, volume should generally increase 
in the direction of the trend. In an uptrend,  

929
01:39:36,000 --> 01:39:40,320
volume should be higher on 
up days. In a downtrend,  

930
01:39:40,320 --> 01:39:46,000
volume should be higher on down days. But 
it's not just about whether volume is high  

931
01:39:46,000 --> 01:39:53,120
or low. The spread (the body of the price bar) 
matters, too. Wyckoff and later traders like  

932
01:39:53,120 --> 01:39:59,760
Tom Williams saw the relationship between 
volume and spread. Here's what to look for:

933
01:39:59,760 --> 01:40:08,480
Wide spread and high volume: usually bullish.
Wide spread and high volume (down): usually  

934
01:40:08,480 --> 01:40:10,960
bearish.
Narrow spread  

935
01:40:10,960 --> 01:40:18,160
and low volume: often means consolidation.
One common pattern is a Climax. This is a  

936
01:40:18,160 --> 01:40:25,600
day with very high volume and a wide price range. 
It often marks the end of a move. In a downtrend,  

937
01:40:25,600 --> 01:40:30,960
it might be a selling climax marking 
the end of the drop. In an uptrend,  

938
01:40:30,960 --> 01:40:38,240
it could be a buying climax signaling the end 
of the rise. After a climax, watch for a Test.  

939
01:40:38,240 --> 01:40:45,200
This is when prices return to near the climax 
level but on lower volume. If the test holds,  

940
01:40:45,200 --> 01:40:50,400
it can confirm the end of the old 
trend and the start of a new one.

941
01:40:50,400 --> 01:40:56,560
Volume can also help spot manipulation. If 
you see a big price move on low volume, be  

942
01:40:56,560 --> 01:41:03,680
suspicious. It might be a false move designed to 
trick traders. We'll talk about this later. Real,  

943
01:41:03,680 --> 01:41:11,200
sustainable moves usually come with solid volume. 
In the Wyckoff Method, volume isn't just about  

944
01:41:11,200 --> 01:41:18,080
quantity; it's about quality, too. A day with 
steady buying is different from a day where all  

945
01:41:18,080 --> 01:41:25,680
the volume comes in one big spike. Learn to read 
the quality of volume, not just the quantity.

946
01:41:25,680 --> 01:41:30,560
One key skill is spotting 
divergences between price and volume.  

947
01:41:30,560 --> 01:41:36,240
If prices are making new highs but volume 
is dropping, it can mean the uptrend is  

948
01:41:36,240 --> 01:41:42,640
weakening. If prices are making new lows but 
volume is drying up, the downtrend might be  

949
01:41:42,640 --> 01:41:48,640
running out of steam. Volume patterns can 
also hint at what's coming. For example,  

950
01:41:48,640 --> 01:41:54,880
expanding volume as prices move sideways 
often precedes a breakout. The direction  

951
01:41:54,880 --> 01:42:01,760
of the breakout is uncertain, but the increase 
in volume suggests something big is cooking.

952
01:42:01,760 --> 01:42:07,440
In accumulation, you might see a series 
of high-volume down days that fail to  

953
01:42:07,440 --> 01:42:14,560
push prices lower. This is often followed by 
an upward surge on even higher volume. This  

954
01:42:14,560 --> 01:42:20,800
pattern can signal the end of this phase 
and the start of markup. In distribution,  

955
01:42:20,800 --> 01:42:27,520
you might see a series of high-volume up days 
that fail to push prices higher. This is often  

956
01:42:27,520 --> 01:42:34,160
followed by a downward plunge on even higher 
volume. This pattern can signal the end of  

957
01:42:34,160 --> 01:42:42,800
distribution and the start of markdown. Volume can 
also help with timing. In a strong trend, wait for  

958
01:42:42,800 --> 01:42:49,120
a pullback on lower volume before entering. 
This often provides a good entry point with  

959
01:42:49,120 --> 01:42:57,520
lower risk. And one final point about this: volume 
often leads price. You might see volume patterns  

960
01:42:57,520 --> 01:43:05,200
change before price patterns do. This can give 
you an early warning of potential trend changes.

961
01:43:05,200 --> 01:43:11,360
The Spring and the Upthrust are key patterns 
in the Wyckoff Method. A Spring is a quick  

962
01:43:11,360 --> 01:43:18,080
drop below support that bounces back fast. 
An Upthrust is a quick push above resistance  

963
01:43:18,080 --> 01:43:25,520
that fails fast. Both are fake-outs that 
run stops outside support and resistance.  

964
01:43:25,520 --> 01:43:32,720
Smart Money concepts renamed them as liquidity 
sweeps or liquidity runs. Why do they happen?  

965
01:43:32,720 --> 01:43:39,040
Because big players often push price past 
key levels to trigger stop-losses. This  

966
01:43:39,040 --> 01:43:45,840
lets them buy or sell at better prices. It is 
like shaking a tree to make the fruit fall.

967
01:43:45,840 --> 01:43:49,200
Let's look at Springs first. In a trading range,  

968
01:43:49,200 --> 01:43:55,920
price might dip below support. If it jumps back 
up fast, that's a Spring. It means there's strong  

969
01:43:55,920 --> 01:44:02,240
buying down there. It often leads to a 
move up. Here's how to spot a Spring:

970
01:44:02,240 --> 01:44:05,760
Price is in a range.
It breaks below support. 

971
01:44:05,760 --> 01:44:11,440
It doesn't stay there long.
Then it jumps back above support fast. 

972
01:44:11,440 --> 01:44:18,080
Upthrusts are the opposite. Price pops above 
resistance but falls back quickly. It shows  

973
01:44:18,080 --> 01:44:25,280
there is strong selling up there. It often leads 
to a move down. Here's how to spot an Upthrust:

974
01:44:25,280 --> 01:44:29,040
Price is in a range.
It breaks above resistance. 

975
01:44:29,040 --> 01:44:34,240
It doesn't stay there long.
Then it drops back below resistance fast. 

976
01:44:34,240 --> 01:44:41,040
Both patterns show a fight between buyers and 
sellers. In a Spring, sellers try to push price  

977
01:44:41,040 --> 01:44:49,440
down, but buyers win. In an Upthrust, buyers try 
to push price up, but sellers win. For a Spring,  

978
01:44:49,440 --> 01:44:55,920
the plan is to buy when price jumps back above 
support. For an Upthrust, you sell when price  

979
01:44:55,920 --> 01:45:02,240
drops back below resistance. But it's not always 
that easy. You need to look at the bigger picture,  

980
01:45:02,240 --> 01:45:08,880
too. For Springs, check if the overall 
trend is up. A Spring in an uptrend is  

981
01:45:08,880 --> 01:45:15,040
stronger than one in a downtrend. Look for 
signs of accumulation before the Spring.  

982
01:45:15,040 --> 01:45:21,040
This makes the pattern more likely to work. 
For Upthrusts, check if the overall trend is  

983
01:45:21,040 --> 01:45:27,440
down. An Upthrust in a downtrend is stronger 
than one in an uptrend. Look for signs of  

984
01:45:27,440 --> 01:45:33,040
distribution before the Upthrust. This 
makes the pattern more likely to work.

985
01:45:33,040 --> 01:45:39,440
Volume is key in these patterns. In a Spring, 
you want to see high volume on the drop and  

986
01:45:39,440 --> 01:45:45,600
even higher volume on the bounce. This 
shows strong buying. In an Upthrust,  

987
01:45:45,600 --> 01:45:51,520
you want high volume on the push-up and 
even higher on the drop. This shows strong  

988
01:45:51,520 --> 01:45:59,120
selling. Some traders do well without focusing 
on volume; the price action itself can be enough.  

989
01:45:59,120 --> 01:46:06,560
The context matters a lot. A Spring or Upthrust 
at the end of a long trend is more powerful than  

990
01:46:06,560 --> 01:46:13,520
one in the middle of a range. It might signal 
a big trend change. One trick is to look for  

991
01:46:13,520 --> 01:46:20,960
smaller ranges near the edge of bigger ranges. 
These often lead to good breakouts. You might see  

992
01:46:20,960 --> 01:46:28,000
Springs or Upthrusts in these smaller ranges 
before a big move. Sometimes you won't see  

993
01:46:28,000 --> 01:46:35,040
a Spring or Upthrust at all. This is called a 
Structural Failure. It happens when price fails  

994
01:46:35,040 --> 01:46:42,320
to reach one side of a range and then breaks out 
the other way. This can be a strong signal, too.

995
01:46:42,320 --> 01:46:48,160
Fibonacci's effectiveness depends on how you 
apply them. And the key is to use them on the  

996
01:46:48,160 --> 01:46:53,920
correct price swings. When you're looking at 
a price chart, you'll see many price swings.  

997
01:46:53,920 --> 01:47:00,320
You might connect two points on the chart that 
seem significant to you, but another trader might  

998
01:47:00,320 --> 01:47:06,800
choose different points. This doesn't mean one of 
you is wrong; it just highlights the subjective  

999
01:47:06,800 --> 01:47:13,360
nature of this tool. To apply Fib retracements 
correctly, you need to start by determining the  

1000
01:47:13,360 --> 01:47:19,600
dominant trend. Once you've identified the 
trend, your next step is to find the most  

1001
01:47:19,600 --> 01:47:26,880
obvious swing high and swing low. These are the 
points you'll use to draw your Fibonacci lines.

1002
01:47:26,880 --> 01:47:32,240
In a bullish trend, you'll draw the Fib 
retracement from the swing low to the swing  

1003
01:47:32,240 --> 01:47:38,400
high. This makes sense because in an uptrend, 
you're looking for potential support levels  

1004
01:47:38,400 --> 01:47:45,440
where the price might pause or reverse during a 
pullback. In a bearish trend, you'll draw from  

1005
01:47:45,440 --> 01:47:51,760
the swing high to the swing low. You're looking 
for potential resistance levels where the price  

1006
01:47:51,760 --> 01:47:58,400
might stall or reverse during a bounce. When 
drawing these lines, it's important to use the  

1007
01:47:58,400 --> 01:48:05,040
wicks of the candlesticks for your swings, not 
just the bodies. The clarity of your chosen swing  

1008
01:48:05,040 --> 01:48:11,280
points is probably the most important aspect. 
The clearer the swing low and high, and the  

1009
01:48:11,280 --> 01:48:17,360
more defined the trend between these points, the 
more reliable your Fib levels are likely to be.

1010
01:48:17,920 --> 01:48:25,600
One common mistake is trying to force Fib levels 
to fit where they don't naturally apply. Remember,  

1011
01:48:25,600 --> 01:48:32,240
not every price move will align perfectly with 
Fib levels, and that's okay. The most helpful  

1012
01:48:32,240 --> 01:48:38,640
Fib retracements are those that are obvious 
on the chart without much effort to spot them.  

1013
01:48:38,640 --> 01:48:45,040
If you find yourself squinting at the chart or 
trying to convince yourself that a level fits,  

1014
01:48:45,040 --> 01:48:48,560
it might be best to look for a clearer setup.

1015
01:48:48,560 --> 01:48:55,840
When applying Fibonacci retracements, think about 
the market structure. In an uptrend, for example,  

1016
01:48:55,840 --> 01:49:02,800
you might look for buying opportunities near 
these Fib levels as the price pulls back. The  

1017
01:49:02,800 --> 01:49:08,960
idea is that the trend will eventually continue 
and these retracement levels offer potential  

1018
01:49:08,960 --> 01:49:16,400
entry points at a better price. Number one rule 
is that Fibonacci levels work best in trending  

1019
01:49:16,400 --> 01:49:24,160
markets. Without a clear trend, these levels lose 
their significance and impact on price movement.

1020
01:49:24,160 --> 01:49:30,400
When you spot a trend, look for the logical 
price swings to place your Fib retracement tool.  

1021
01:49:30,400 --> 01:49:36,320
This step is critical and often where most 
traders struggle. The trick is to find the  

1022
01:49:36,320 --> 01:49:43,680
most relevant high and low points that represent 
the current market conditions. So in this uptrend,  

1023
01:49:43,680 --> 01:49:48,800
I would draw the Fib retracement from 
this swing low to this swing high. For  

1024
01:49:48,800 --> 01:49:53,920
this downtrend, I would draw it from 
this swing high to the swing low.

1025
01:49:53,920 --> 01:49:59,600
Once you've placed your Fib levels, you'll 
notice several key retracement levels.  

1026
01:49:59,600 --> 01:50:07,360
The most commonly used are 23.6%, 38.2%, 
50%, and 61.8% levels. These lines can act  

1027
01:50:07,360 --> 01:50:14,800
as potential support areas in an uptrend 
or resistance zones in a downtrend. Many  

1028
01:50:14,800 --> 01:50:22,720
traders focus primarily on the 61.8% retracement 
level as it's often considered the Golden Ratio,  

1029
01:50:22,720 --> 01:50:29,040
but I wouldn't discount the power of other 
levels. In strong trends, price might only  

1030
01:50:29,040 --> 01:50:36,400
retrace to the 38.2% level before continuing 
in the trend direction. In weaker trends,  

1031
01:50:36,400 --> 01:50:44,560
price might extend to the 78.6% level. Now, it's 
worth noting that these Fibonacci levels don't act  

1032
01:50:44,560 --> 01:50:52,480
as exact support or resistance points. Instead, 
they help you find areas where price might react.  

1033
01:50:52,480 --> 01:51:00,320
So think of them as zones rather than precise 
lines. Remember, Fibonacci levels often become  

1034
01:51:00,320 --> 01:51:06,240
self-fulfilling prophecies in the market. 
Many traders watch these same levels. This  

1035
01:51:06,240 --> 01:51:12,160
collective action can create real support 
and resistance zones. And please note that  

1036
01:51:12,160 --> 01:51:18,960
Fib levels struggle in sideways or ranging 
conditions. If the market is consolidating,  

1037
01:51:18,960 --> 01:51:25,520
it's often better to wait for a clear 
breakout before applying a Fibonacci analysis.

1038
01:51:25,520 --> 01:51:31,200
Here's another common mistake: when you 
apply Fibonacci retracements to very small  

1039
01:51:31,200 --> 01:51:38,800
price moves or shorter timeframes, you might run 
into some issues that can make your trading less  

1040
01:51:38,800 --> 01:51:46,000
effective. Think about it this way: on shorter 
timeframes, price movements are often more erratic  

1041
01:51:46,000 --> 01:51:52,560
and less significant. These small, rapid price 
changes don't always reflect the true market  

1042
01:51:52,560 --> 01:51:59,520
trend or important levels. When you try to use 
Fibonacci retracements on these short-term moves,  

1043
01:51:59,520 --> 01:52:06,560
the levels you get are often too close together. 
This closeness makes it hard to tell which levels  

1044
01:52:06,560 --> 01:52:13,280
are truly important and which are just noise. 
Another problem with using Fibonacci on short  

1045
01:52:13,280 --> 01:52:19,280
timeframes is that you're more likely to see 
false breakouts and price spikes. These quick,  

1046
01:52:19,280 --> 01:52:25,200
sharp moves can trick you into thinking a 
level has been broken when it hasn't really.  

1047
01:52:25,200 --> 01:52:32,320
This can lead to poor signals like entering 
a trade too early or exiting one too soon.

1048
01:52:32,320 --> 01:52:37,920
Think about it. Stops and take-profit 
points are key for managing your trades.  

1049
01:52:37,920 --> 01:52:43,600
But when you use Fib retracements on short 
timeframes, it becomes tricky to place these  

1050
01:52:43,600 --> 01:52:48,960
effectively. The retracement levels are 
so close together that they create narrow  

1051
01:52:48,960 --> 01:52:54,800
confluences. This means there's not much 
room between levels, making it hard to set  

1052
01:52:54,800 --> 01:53:01,440
stops that protect you from normal market noise 
while still giving your trade room to breathe.

1053
01:53:01,440 --> 01:53:07,440
So, what's the solution? Focus on larger 
timeframes. When you apply Fib levels,  

1054
01:53:07,440 --> 01:53:13,760
you get a clearer view of the long-term trend. 
This helps you apply Fibonacci retracements in  

1055
01:53:13,760 --> 01:53:20,320
the right direction, aligning with the overall 
market movement. When you use Fib retracements  

1056
01:53:20,320 --> 01:53:26,320
on larger timeframes, you're looking at more 
significant price moves. These bigger swings  

1057
01:53:26,320 --> 01:53:32,640
are more likely to represent important market 
levels. The levels drawn on these larger moves  

1058
01:53:32,640 --> 01:53:40,080
are spaced further apart, making it easier to see 
which levels might be important. And you don't  

1059
01:53:40,080 --> 01:53:46,000
have to stick to just one timeframe. You can use 
a Multi-Timeframe Approach. You might start with  

1060
01:53:46,000 --> 01:53:53,280
a larger timeframe to find the overall trend and 
major Fibonacci levels, then zoom in to a smaller  

1061
01:53:53,280 --> 01:54:00,560
timeframe. Another benefit of placing Fibs on 
larger timeframes is that it can help you avoid  

1062
01:54:00,560 --> 01:54:07,200
overtrading. When you focus on smaller moves, 
it's tempting to take many trades, thinking each  

1063
01:54:07,200 --> 01:54:14,080
small retracement is significant. But by zooming 
out and looking at the bigger picture, you can  

1064
01:54:14,080 --> 01:54:21,440
be more selective with your trades, focusing on 
the moves that are more likely to be significant.

1065
01:54:21,440 --> 01:54:28,960
When we talk about retracements, we are looking at 
how much a price pulls back after a strong move.  

1066
01:54:28,960 --> 01:54:32,640
These pullbacks can be shallow or deep.

1067
01:54:32,640 --> 01:54:38,560
Shallow Retracements happen in strong trends. 
When a market is moving with conviction,  

1068
01:54:38,560 --> 01:54:44,240
it doesn't pull back much before 
continuing its journey. In these cases,  

1069
01:54:44,240 --> 01:54:50,880
you'll often see the price only retreat 
to the 23.6% or 38.2% areas. The trend  

1070
01:54:50,880 --> 01:54:56,560
is so strong that it doesn't need much 
time to refuel before zooming off again.  

1071
01:54:56,560 --> 01:55:03,440
When you spot these shallow pullbacks, it's a sign 
that the trend is healthy and likely to continue.

1072
01:55:03,440 --> 01:55:09,120
Deep Retracements are more common when 
a trend isn't fully established yet. The  

1073
01:55:09,120 --> 01:55:15,200
price might make several ups and downs, 
testing previous highs or lows without  

1074
01:55:15,200 --> 01:55:23,600
breaking them. Deep retracements often reach 
the 61.8%, 78.6%, or even 88.6% Fib levels.  

1075
01:55:23,600 --> 01:55:29,360
And these deeper pullbacks can be tricky. 
They might make you think the trend is over,  

1076
01:55:29,360 --> 01:55:34,880
but it's not always the case. It's more 
like the market is taking a longer break,  

1077
01:55:34,880 --> 01:55:39,760
perhaps reassessing its direction 
before deciding to continue.

1078
01:55:39,760 --> 01:55:44,480
The key difference between shallow and 
deep retracements is in what they tell  

1079
01:55:44,480 --> 01:55:51,280
us about the strength of the trend. Shallow 
retracements signal a strong, confident trend.  

1080
01:55:51,280 --> 01:55:59,280
The market barely hesitates before pushing on. 
Deep retracements suggest more uncertainty. The  

1081
01:55:59,280 --> 01:56:05,280
trend might still continue, but it's taking its 
time to gather strength. If you see a shallow  

1082
01:56:05,280 --> 01:56:10,800
retracement in a strong trend, it might be a 
good opportunity to join in the direction of  

1083
01:56:10,800 --> 01:56:17,680
that trend. With deep retracements, you might 
need to be more cautious. While they can still  

1084
01:56:17,680 --> 01:56:24,320
lead to continuation of the trend, there's also 
a higher chance the trend might be losing steam.  

1085
01:56:24,320 --> 01:56:32,880
And if the price retraces 100% of the last move, 
it might be a sign that the trend has failed.

1086
01:56:32,880 --> 01:56:38,480
Now, when price reaches a Fib level, 
look for specific candlestick patterns.  

1087
01:56:38,480 --> 01:56:43,520
These patterns can confirm if the 
level is likely to hold or break.  

1088
01:56:43,520 --> 01:56:49,120
It's like getting a second opinion before 
making a trade. There are a lot of candlesticks,  

1089
01:56:49,120 --> 01:56:56,160
but the most useful patterns at Fib levels are 
Engulfing Patterns and Candles with Long Wicks.

1090
01:56:56,160 --> 01:57:02,480
Candles with a long lower wick show up at the 
end of a down move. This long wick shows that  

1091
01:57:02,480 --> 01:57:08,400
sellers tried to push price lower, but 
buyers stepped in and pushed it back up.  

1092
01:57:08,400 --> 01:57:15,040
When you see it at a Fibonacci support level, it 
might mean the down move is over. If you spot a  

1093
01:57:15,040 --> 01:57:21,280
candle with a long upper wick at a Fibonacci 
resistance level, pay close attention. They  

1094
01:57:21,280 --> 01:57:28,720
often signal the end of up moves. Buyers try 
to push price higher, but sellers took control.

1095
01:57:28,720 --> 01:57:34,560
Engulfing patterns are also decent 
signals. In a bullish engulfing pattern,  

1096
01:57:34,560 --> 01:57:40,800
a large green candle completely covers 
the previous red candle. This shows buyers  

1097
01:57:40,800 --> 01:57:48,080
taking control from sellers. A bearish engulfing 
pattern is the opposite, with a large red candle  

1098
01:57:48,080 --> 01:57:55,360
covering the previous green one. These patterns at 
Fibonacci levels can be strong reversal signals.

1099
01:57:56,000 --> 01:58:01,920
From my experience, using candlesticks 
with Fibonacci levels works best on  

1100
01:58:01,920 --> 01:58:07,840
longer timeframes. This is because bigger 
moves tend to respect Fib levels more,  

1101
01:58:07,840 --> 01:58:14,880
and candlestick patterns on longer timeframes 
often carry more weight. Let's say price is in  

1102
01:58:14,880 --> 01:58:22,800
an uptrend and pulls back to the 50% Fib level. 
This level acts as a potential support. If you see  

1103
01:58:22,800 --> 01:58:28,960
a candle with a long candlestick forming right at 
this level, it's a decent sign that the pullback  

1104
01:58:28,960 --> 01:58:35,440
might be over. The Fib level shows where buyers 
might step in, and the candle shows that they  

1105
01:58:35,440 --> 01:58:44,320
actually did. Here, price is in a downtrend 
and bounces up to the 38.2% Fib level. This  

1106
01:58:44,320 --> 01:58:50,800
level will act as a potential resistance in a 
downtrend. If an engulfing candle forms here,  

1107
01:58:50,800 --> 01:58:57,280
it implies the bounce might be over. So the 
Fib level shows where sellers might return,  

1108
01:58:57,280 --> 01:59:03,760
and the engulfing candle shows they're actually 
taking control. These engulfing patterns at  

1109
01:59:03,760 --> 01:59:10,240
Fib levels show a sudden, strong shift in who's 
controlling the market. And an engulfing pattern  

1110
01:59:10,240 --> 01:59:17,280
that completely swallows several previous candles 
at a key Fibonacci level is hard to ignore.

1111
01:59:18,080 --> 01:59:24,560
Volume can add another layer of confirmation 
to candlestick patterns at Fibonacci levels.  

1112
01:59:24,560 --> 01:59:31,600
A reversal candle with high volume at a Fibonacci 
support level is more convincing than one with low  

1113
01:59:31,600 --> 01:59:38,000
volume. The high volume shows strong buying 
interest right where buyers were expected to  

1114
01:59:38,000 --> 01:59:47,440
step in. Now, one common mistake is to focus only 
on exact Fibonacci levels. As I said, in reality,  

1115
01:59:47,440 --> 01:59:53,680
these levels are more like zones than exact 
lines. A candlestick pattern doesn't have to  

1116
01:59:53,680 --> 02:00:01,680
form exactly at a Fib level to be valid. If it's 
close, it's worth paying attention to. And another  

1117
02:00:01,680 --> 02:00:08,000
key point is to look at the bigger picture. 
A candlestick pattern at a Fib level is more  

1118
02:00:08,000 --> 02:00:15,120
meaningful if it aligns with the larger trend. 
For example, a bullish pattern at a Fibonacci  

1119
02:00:15,120 --> 02:00:23,360
support level in an overall uptrend is typically 
stronger than one that goes against the trend.

1120
02:00:23,360 --> 02:00:30,720
The Golden Zone Method is a smart way to trade 
using Fibonacci levels. This method focuses on  

1121
02:00:30,720 --> 02:00:37,920
the 50% and 61.8% area, which we call the 
Golden Ratio. First, you find a clear trend  

1122
02:00:37,920 --> 02:00:44,720
in the market. You then apply Fibonacci tools 
to this trend. You've practically marked the  

1123
02:00:44,720 --> 02:00:50,320
key levels where the price might turn around. 
The strategy gets interesting when the price  

1124
02:00:50,320 --> 02:00:57,440
starts to move against the trend. When price 
starts going up, you watch closely as it moves  

1125
02:00:57,440 --> 02:01:05,920
past the 50% Fib level. The key is to see if the 
price can break and close above the 61.8% level.  

1126
02:01:05,920 --> 02:01:11,680
In the perfect scenario, the price reaches 
the zone but doesn't close above it. And  

1127
02:01:11,680 --> 02:01:17,600
this could be a signal that the downtrend 
is ready to continue. In the real market,  

1128
02:01:17,600 --> 02:01:25,200
the price will touch and even go a bit above this 
area, but this doesn't invalidate the setup. So,  

1129
02:01:25,200 --> 02:01:32,160
it's okay if the price goes above the 61.8 line. 
Once it returns below it, that's a good sign for  

1130
02:01:32,160 --> 02:01:38,800
our strategy. This moment is when we get ready 
to make a move. We are looking for signs that  

1131
02:01:38,800 --> 02:01:46,080
the price is about to turn back down. Maybe it's a 
bearish candle forming or other factors lining up.  

1132
02:01:46,080 --> 02:01:53,520
The idea is to catch the market just as it's 
deciding to follow the original trend again.

1133
02:01:53,520 --> 02:02:00,000
In this chart, once we see the price bounce off 
the Golden Zone, we start looking for a move back  

1134
02:02:00,000 --> 02:02:08,640
up. The next target might be the 38.2% Fibonacci 
level. If the price breaks above the 38.2% level,  

1135
02:02:08,640 --> 02:02:14,880
it could mean the previous uptrend is picking 
up steam again. After the 38.2% level,  

1136
02:02:14,880 --> 02:02:22,000
the next stop might be the 23.6% level. This 
is another place where the price might pause or  

1137
02:02:22,000 --> 02:02:29,040
bounce a little. But if the uptrend is strong, 
even this level might not hold. In that case,  

1138
02:02:29,040 --> 02:02:34,960
we could see the price go all the way back to 
where the downward move started. We call this  

1139
02:02:34,960 --> 02:02:43,280
a 100% retracement. So, these Fib levels aren't 
just targets for where the price might go. They're  

1140
02:02:43,280 --> 02:02:50,480
also useful for managing your trade. You can use 
these levels to decide when to take some profits.  

1141
02:02:50,480 --> 02:02:55,680
For instance, you might decide to sell a 
part of your position when the price hits  

1142
02:02:55,680 --> 02:03:04,480
the 38.2% level and more at a 23.6% level. If 
the price never got higher than the Golden Zone,  

1143
02:03:04,480 --> 02:03:09,040
you might put your stop-loss 
just above that line. This way,  

1144
02:03:09,040 --> 02:03:14,560
if the market suddenly changes direction 
after you entered, you're protected.

1145
02:03:15,360 --> 02:03:21,520
Fibonacci and Moving Averages Combo is 
also a viable method. When used together,  

1146
02:03:21,520 --> 02:03:28,400
they create a synergy that can confirm your 
signals. Fibonacci alone can point to possible  

1147
02:03:28,400 --> 02:03:34,160
support or resistance levels, but they lack 
the weight of confirmation. This is where  

1148
02:03:34,160 --> 02:03:41,680
moving averages step in, adding an extra layer of 
validation to your analysis. Moving averages serve  

1149
02:03:41,680 --> 02:03:49,040
two key purposes in this partnership. First, they 
help you spot trends. A simple look at the slope  

1150
02:03:49,040 --> 02:03:56,560
of a moving average can tell you if the market is 
trending up, down, or sideways. And second, moving  

1151
02:03:56,560 --> 02:04:05,120
averages act as dynamic support and resistance. As 
price moves, these lines shift, creating flexible  

1152
02:04:05,120 --> 02:04:12,080
barriers that price often respects. And when a 
Fibonacci level lines up with a moving average,  

1153
02:04:12,080 --> 02:04:19,120
you've found a spot of Confluence. In this 
example, price has been climbing steadily.  

1154
02:04:19,120 --> 02:04:26,320
You draw your Fibonacci retracement from the 
recent low to the high. The 50% retracement level  

1155
02:04:26,320 --> 02:04:32,880
catches your eye. Now you notice the 200-period 
Exponential Moving Average (EMA) is sitting  

1156
02:04:32,880 --> 02:04:39,200
right at that same level. This is confluence 
in action. The Fibonacci tool and the moving  

1157
02:04:39,200 --> 02:04:46,000
average are both pointing to the same price 
area as significant. This confluence increases  

1158
02:04:46,000 --> 02:04:52,960
the odds of price reacting at this level. You 
might see price pause, bounce, or even reverse  

1159
02:04:52,960 --> 02:05:00,240
at this point. It's not a guarantee, but it's a 
strong hint from the market. This combination is  

1160
02:05:00,240 --> 02:05:06,720
powerful because Fib retracements can sometimes 
seem arbitrary, and moving averages on their  

1161
02:05:06,720 --> 02:05:15,200
own can lag behind price action, but together 
they create a more robust analytical framework.

1162
02:05:15,200 --> 02:05:21,040
Probably my favorite strategy is to look for 
confluences between the Fib levels and Supply  

1163
02:05:21,040 --> 02:05:27,440
or Demand Areas. It doesn't happen often, but 
when it does, it can be a sign of something  

1164
02:05:27,440 --> 02:05:35,280
special. In this example, notice that the price is 
approaching a key demand area that lines up with  

1165
02:05:35,280 --> 02:05:42,160
a Fib level. That's a confluence perfect for 
a trade. If the price bounces off that area,  

1166
02:05:42,160 --> 02:05:48,720
it could be the start of a beautiful uptrend 
that you can ride. On the flip side, if you  

1167
02:05:48,720 --> 02:05:54,720
see the price approaching a major supply 
area and that coincides with a Fib level,  

1168
02:05:54,720 --> 02:05:59,600
it could be a sign that the buyers are 
about to run out of steam. If the price  

1169
02:05:59,600 --> 02:06:06,160
gets rejected at that level, it might be time 
to start hunting for short opportunities.

1170
02:06:06,160 --> 02:06:12,560
Let's talk about demand areas first. These are 
places where lots of people want to buy. When  

1171
02:06:12,560 --> 02:06:20,000
the price gets near a demand area and it's also 
close to a Fibonacci level, it's extra special.  

1172
02:06:20,000 --> 02:06:26,800
This tells us that the price might start going up 
soon. Think about it like this: you're looking at  

1173
02:06:26,800 --> 02:06:33,200
an uptrend. Then the price is going down, but 
then you notice it's getting close to a demand  

1174
02:06:33,200 --> 02:06:41,280
area. The price is also near a key Fibonacci 
level. You may want to monitor closely this area.

1175
02:06:42,320 --> 02:06:49,440
Supply areas are spots where lots of people want 
to sell. When the price climbs up to a supply area  

1176
02:06:49,440 --> 02:06:56,000
and it matches a Fibonacci level, it's another 
special moment. This might mean the price is  

1177
02:06:56,000 --> 02:07:03,680
about to turn around and start falling. Picture 
this: the market is in a general downtrend. Then  

1178
02:07:03,680 --> 02:07:10,320
the price has been climbing for a while. Then you 
see it's approaching a supply area. The price is  

1179
02:07:10,320 --> 02:07:17,200
also near an important Fibonacci level. This is 
when you start thinking the upward move might be  

1180
02:07:17,200 --> 02:07:24,160
running out of steam. These confluences are like 
secret messages in the market. They don't happen  

1181
02:07:24,160 --> 02:07:31,280
all the time, but when they do, you pay attention. 
Here, price bounced off a demand area that lines  

1182
02:07:31,280 --> 02:07:37,600
up with the Fibonacci level. This is a good time 
to enter a buy position and ride the price up as  

1183
02:07:37,600 --> 02:07:45,680
it starts a new upward move. And here price hit 
a supply area that matches a Fibonacci level  

1184
02:07:45,680 --> 02:07:53,440
and then started to fall. This was a good time 
to sell as price started a new downward move.

1185
02:07:53,440 --> 02:07:59,120
We'll start with the Engulfing Momentum 
Candlestick. This signal occurs when a large  

1186
02:07:59,120 --> 02:08:06,640
candle fully engulfs the body of the previous two 
candles. Basically, a big candle that completely  

1187
02:08:06,640 --> 02:08:12,800
covers the smaller ones right before it. 
This isn't just a regular occurrence. It's  

1188
02:08:12,800 --> 02:08:20,240
a sign—a clear indicator of a strong move in the 
market. This is what we call an engulfing pattern.  

1189
02:08:20,240 --> 02:08:26,080
The psychology behind this pattern is all about 
market sentiment and the sudden shift in the  

1190
02:08:26,080 --> 02:08:31,680
balance between buyers and sellers. 
Before an engulfing pattern occurs,  

1191
02:08:31,680 --> 02:08:37,440
there usually is a clear trend. This trend 
indicates a prevailing direction where  

1192
02:08:37,440 --> 02:08:43,440
the majority of market participants are 
either buying or selling. At some point,  

1193
02:08:43,440 --> 02:08:50,000
the market starts showing signs of exhaustion. 
For a bullish engulfing momentum bar, this might  

1194
02:08:50,000 --> 02:08:56,080
be at a support area or at a demand zone where 
buyers believe the price is attractive enough  

1195
02:08:56,080 --> 02:09:02,640
to start buying in large quantities. For a 
bearish engulfing one, this could be at a  

1196
02:09:02,640 --> 02:09:10,240
resistance or at a supply zone where sellers feel 
the price has peaked and it's a good time to sell.

1197
02:09:10,240 --> 02:09:17,200
The engulfing momentum candle represents a strong 
shift in sentiment. If it's bullish, buyers have  

1198
02:09:17,200 --> 02:09:23,920
overwhelmed the sellers, pushing the price up and 
covering the range of the previous two candles.  

1199
02:09:23,920 --> 02:09:30,400
This suggests that the demand has suddenly 
outstripped the supply. In a bearish pattern,  

1200
02:09:30,400 --> 02:09:37,280
sellers have come in strong, indicating an excess 
of supply over demand. The immediate effect of an  

1201
02:09:37,280 --> 02:09:44,400
engulfing momentum bar is to signal a potential 
reversal. It shows a decisive change in market  

1202
02:09:44,400 --> 02:09:51,680
dynamics. For bullish signals, it could mean the 
end of a downtrend phase with prices likely to  

1203
02:09:51,680 --> 02:09:59,600
rise. For bearish ones, it could suggest the end 
of an uptrend wave with prices expected to fall.

1204
02:09:59,600 --> 02:10:04,720
The Long-Wick Engulfing Candlestick 
is my favorite price action strategy.  

1205
02:10:04,720 --> 02:10:11,040
This candlestick not only indicates a strong 
rejection of prices but also signals a potential  

1206
02:10:11,040 --> 02:10:17,360
momentum shift in the market direction. This 
candle typically shows a large body with a long  

1207
02:10:17,360 --> 02:10:23,760
wick that extends far beyond the body's edges. 
The engulfing part means that the body of this  

1208
02:10:23,760 --> 02:10:31,280
candle is larger than the body of the previous 
candle, completely overshadowing or engulfing it.  

1209
02:10:31,280 --> 02:10:36,320
This visual on your chart is your first 
clue about a significant shift in market  

1210
02:10:36,320 --> 02:10:42,080
sentiment. The long wick represents a 
point where supply surpasses demand,  

1211
02:10:42,080 --> 02:10:48,400
pushing the price back down (or vice versa, 
depending on the direction of the wick).

1212
02:10:48,400 --> 02:10:54,960
Let's say the long wick is at the top of the 
candle. This suggests that as the price went up,  

1213
02:10:54,960 --> 02:11:00,880
it hit a level where sellers were waiting to 
take profits or considered the price too high,  

1214
02:11:00,880 --> 02:11:06,960
outweighing buyers. This results in the 
price being pushed back down sharply,  

1215
02:11:06,960 --> 02:11:14,160
leaving behind a long upper wick. The rejection 
indicated by the long wick is significant because  

1216
02:11:14,160 --> 02:11:20,560
it shows that a certain price level could not 
be sustained. Buyers tried to push the price up,  

1217
02:11:20,560 --> 02:11:26,160
but the overwhelming number of sellers 
at that level rejected this move. If the  

1218
02:11:26,160 --> 02:11:32,800
candle also engulfed the previous candle, it 
shows increasing selling momentum despite any  

1219
02:11:32,800 --> 02:11:38,800
buying pressure that might have been present 
initially. Sellers took control and managed  

1220
02:11:38,800 --> 02:11:46,640
to push the closing price below the open one of 
the previous candle, indicating strong supply.

1221
02:11:46,640 --> 02:11:53,120
If the wick is at the bottom, it means sellers 
drove the price down. But buyers stepped in,  

1222
02:11:53,120 --> 02:11:58,800
finding the lower price attractive, thus 
pushing the price back up, showing rejection  

1223
02:11:58,800 --> 02:12:05,760
of lower prices. If the body of the candlestick 
also engulfs the previous candle, it suggests  

1224
02:12:05,760 --> 02:12:12,560
increasing buying momentum. Buyers were not only 
able to overcome the selling pressure indicated by  

1225
02:12:12,560 --> 02:12:18,160
the long upper wick, but were also strong enough 
to close the candle higher than the previous  

1226
02:12:18,160 --> 02:12:25,280
candle's body, indicating strong demand. This 
is a powerful price action signal. It provides  

1227
02:12:25,280 --> 02:12:31,360
a clear signal that the market sentiment might 
be changing direction. Look for these patterns  

1228
02:12:31,360 --> 02:12:38,640
at major resistance or support levels because they 
can signal the end of a trend or the reversal of a  

1229
02:12:38,640 --> 02:12:46,000
price direction. A bullish long-wick engulfing 
candle at a key support level might suggest a  

1230
02:12:46,000 --> 02:12:52,320
potential upward reversal, tempting buyers 
to enter the market expecting future gains.

1231
02:12:53,040 --> 02:12:58,000
When you see multiple rejection wicks 
and candles are changing their color,  

1232
02:12:58,000 --> 02:13:04,400
you are witnessing a strong signal. In this 
example, observe these two consecutive candles  

1233
02:13:04,400 --> 02:13:10,800
at a similar price level where the first is 
bullish with a long upper wick followed by  

1234
02:13:10,800 --> 02:13:17,760
a bearish one with a similar long upper wick. 
This formation can tell you a lot about what's  

1235
02:13:17,760 --> 02:13:23,920
happening in the market. Starting with supply 
and demand, the first candle (the bullish one  

1236
02:13:23,920 --> 02:13:29,840
with a long upper wick) indicates that 
buyers initially pushed prices higher.  

1237
02:13:29,840 --> 02:13:36,320
The long upper wick shows that as the price 
reached higher levels, an ample supply emerged,  

1238
02:13:36,320 --> 02:13:42,960
overpowering the buyers and pushing the price 
down from its peak before the candle closed. At  

1239
02:13:42,960 --> 02:13:49,200
these higher price levels, sellers are more 
than willing to step in and take control.

1240
02:13:49,200 --> 02:13:55,920
Now when the next candle opens, it starts where 
the first one left off but turns bearish with  

1241
02:13:55,920 --> 02:14:02,800
a long upper wick as well. This second candle 
confirms the presence of strong selling interest  

1242
02:14:02,800 --> 02:14:08,800
at these levels. The fact that this candle is 
bearish and mirrors the wick of the previous  

1243
02:14:08,800 --> 02:14:15,440
bullish candle intensifies the signal. The 
sellers are not just reacting spontaneously.  

1244
02:14:15,440 --> 02:14:21,440
They are firmly establishing their ground, showing 
that they are prepared to sell at these prices,  

1245
02:14:21,440 --> 02:14:28,480
thus increasing the supply. The repeated rejection 
at this price level signifies that the supply has  

1246
02:14:28,480 --> 02:14:35,760
surpassed the demand, possibly leading to a trend 
reversal or at least a significant pullback. From  

1247
02:14:35,760 --> 02:14:43,040
a psychological perspective, this signal plays 
a vital role. Consider the first bullish candle.  

1248
02:14:43,040 --> 02:14:48,400
Traders who bought during or just before 
the high might have expected the momentum  

1249
02:14:48,400 --> 02:14:54,880
to continue. The subsequent price dip could 
lead to a change in sentiment from optimism  

1250
02:14:54,880 --> 02:15:02,240
to concern or even fear. This emotional shift 
is crucial as it might prompt those buyers to  

1251
02:15:02,240 --> 02:15:08,560
sell quickly to cut losses when they see prices 
failing to go higher, which adds to the selling  

1252
02:15:08,560 --> 02:15:14,800
pressure. If this pattern appears at a known 
resistance level, the message it sends is even  

1253
02:15:14,800 --> 02:15:20,800
stronger. Traders often place their stops 
around these levels, and the activation of  

1254
02:15:20,800 --> 02:15:27,920
these stops can accelerate the price movement 
downward as the bearish sentiment takes hold.

1255
02:15:27,920 --> 02:15:33,040
The Over and Under Pattern is one of the 
most effective price action strategies.  

1256
02:15:33,040 --> 02:15:38,560
This pattern essentially signals a critical 
shift in the market dynamics, hinting at a  

1257
02:15:38,560 --> 02:15:45,440
potential weakening or reversal of a trend. So in 
any trading market, prices are driven by supply  

1258
02:15:45,440 --> 02:15:51,600
and demand. These forces are represented by 
the actions of buyers and sellers who push  

1259
02:15:51,600 --> 02:15:58,880
prices higher or lower. A trend, whether up or 
down, continues as long as there is an imbalance  

1260
02:15:58,880 --> 02:16:06,800
favoring either buyers or sellers. For example, in 
an uptrend, buyers prevail, consistently willing  

1261
02:16:06,800 --> 02:16:13,440
to buy at higher prices, thus creating a 
sequence of higher highs and higher lows.

1262
02:16:13,440 --> 02:16:18,880
The Over and Under pattern comes into play 
when there is a noticeable shift in this trend  

1263
02:16:18,880 --> 02:16:26,000
structure. When the price suddenly drops below a 
previous major low and then makes a lower high,  

1264
02:16:26,000 --> 02:16:32,399
it suggests a break in this structure. This is the 
first clue that the prevailing buying pressure is  

1265
02:16:32,399 --> 02:16:39,679
weakening. The scenario is similar but reversed in 
a downtrend. When prices push above the previous  

1266
02:16:39,680 --> 02:16:46,240
low but then form a higher high, it indicates 
that the selling pressure is diminishing.

1267
02:16:46,240 --> 02:16:52,800
Let's consider the psychological aspects driving 
this pattern. In an uptrend, as the price drops  

1268
02:16:52,800 --> 02:16:58,720
to form what initially appears as a normal 
pullback, buyers are typically prepared to  

1269
02:16:58,720 --> 02:17:05,520
jump in, anticipating another push to higher 
highs. However, as the price fails to reach  

1270
02:17:05,520 --> 02:17:11,920
a new high and instead falls below the previous 
low, it disrupts the expectations formed by the  

1271
02:17:11,920 --> 02:17:19,439
market participants. This unexpected change often 
leads to uncertainty and a shift in sentiment,  

1272
02:17:19,439 --> 02:17:26,080
causing some of the buyers to step back and 
reassess their positions while potential sellers  

1273
02:17:26,080 --> 02:17:32,800
might see an opportunity to enter the market. The 
pivotal moment in the Over and Under pattern is  

1274
02:17:32,800 --> 02:17:38,720
when the price breaches a significant level. 
This action is a powerful signal because it  

1275
02:17:38,720 --> 02:17:44,319
challenges the established market structure. 
It's not just a simple breach; it's a signal  

1276
02:17:44,319 --> 02:17:50,880
that the previous consensus is no longer valid. 
This can lead to rapid shifts in supply and  

1277
02:17:50,880 --> 02:17:58,399
demand. Buyers who were previously supporting 
the price by buying at dips might pull back,  

1278
02:17:58,399 --> 02:18:05,679
and sellers may start to dominate, pushing the 
price down further in what was an uptrend. From  

1279
02:18:05,680 --> 02:18:11,600
a supply and demand perspective, this pattern 
reflects a shift in the balance. The initial  

1280
02:18:11,600 --> 02:18:18,240
move past the previous high increases the demand 
suddenly. But this failure to continue in the same  

1281
02:18:18,240 --> 02:18:26,960
direction indicates exhaustion and the possible 
reversal of roles between buyers and sellers.

1282
02:18:26,960 --> 02:18:34,160
Another important strategy is the Weak Break of 
Structure. This signal is subtle but powerful.  

1283
02:18:34,160 --> 02:18:40,800
Now, a weak break of structure occurs when the 
price marginally surpasses a previous high in  

1284
02:18:40,800 --> 02:18:49,280
an uptrend (or a low in a downtrend) but fails to 
sustain this momentum and quickly retraces. This  

1285
02:18:49,280 --> 02:18:55,120
scenario often indicates that the market does 
not have sufficient conviction to support the  

1286
02:18:55,120 --> 02:19:02,640
new highs or lows, leading to what we call 
a weak break of structure. In any market,  

1287
02:19:02,640 --> 02:19:09,080
price movements are fundamentally driven by the 
imbalance between supply and demand. A weak break  

1288
02:19:09,080 --> 02:19:16,240
of structure typically occurs at points where 
this balance is delicate and easily disrupted.

1289
02:19:16,240 --> 02:19:22,000
Consider a scenario where a price level 
has historically acted as resistance. As  

1290
02:19:22,000 --> 02:19:27,600
prices approach this level, sellers begin 
to dominate the market, believing that the  

1291
02:19:27,600 --> 02:19:34,800
level will hold and prices will drop again. 
Buyers, on the other hand, push the price up,  

1292
02:19:34,800 --> 02:19:40,560
testing the resistance. If the buying pressure 
is strong enough, it might initially break the  

1293
02:19:40,560 --> 02:19:46,880
resistance level. However, if this break is 
weak—meaning it only goes slightly above the  

1294
02:19:46,880 --> 02:19:53,760
resistance level and quickly retraces—it suggests 
that the buying pressure was not truly powerful  

1295
02:19:53,760 --> 02:19:59,920
enough to shift the market sentiment decisively. 
The sellers still have substantial influence,  

1296
02:19:59,920 --> 02:20:06,720
and the demand was not sufficient to maintain the 
higher prices. If the price cannot sustain itself  

1297
02:20:06,720 --> 02:20:14,080
above the previous resistance, it indicates that 
demand is weakening. The price often falls back to  

1298
02:20:14,080 --> 02:20:22,479
lower levels as sellers regain control and buyers 
withdraw, waiting for more favorable conditions.

1299
02:20:22,479 --> 02:20:28,559
One instance of a weak break of structure may 
not be meaningful, but consecutive weak breaks  

1300
02:20:28,560 --> 02:20:35,760
of structure can form a pattern that highlights 
a significant loss of momentum. For instance,  

1301
02:20:35,760 --> 02:20:42,399
if the market attempts to break a low multiple 
times, but each time only succeeds marginally  

1302
02:20:42,399 --> 02:20:48,879
before retracing, it suggests a consistent 
lack of supply at lower price levels.  

1303
02:20:48,880 --> 02:20:52,640
This scenario often precedes a 
stronger move in the opposite  

1304
02:20:52,640 --> 02:21:00,319
direction. Consecutive weak breaks will allow 
you to anticipate potential market turns.

1305
02:21:00,319 --> 02:21:07,519
The next strategy involves finding instances of 
Momentum Gain and Momentum Loss. Momentum refers  

1306
02:21:07,520 --> 02:21:12,960
to the speed or strength of price movements. 
And this can be observed through the lens of  

1307
02:21:12,960 --> 02:21:20,160
consecutive candles increasing or decreasing 
in size from a supply and demand perspective.

1308
02:21:20,160 --> 02:21:25,840
When you see consecutive candles getting 
larger and larger, this usually signals a  

1309
02:21:25,840 --> 02:21:32,800
Momentum Gain. Imagine a scenario where each 
candle represents a day of trading. If each  

1310
02:21:32,800 --> 02:21:38,720
day the price moves higher than the previous 
day and the size of the candle gets bigger,  

1311
02:21:38,720 --> 02:21:45,439
it indicates strong buying pressure; more buyers 
are entering the market, willing to buy at even  

1312
02:21:45,439 --> 02:21:53,120
higher prices. This buying pressure pushes 
the price up, creating larger bullish candles.  

1313
02:21:53,120 --> 02:21:58,319
This can often be seen in an uptrend 
where each candle is getting larger  

1314
02:21:58,319 --> 02:22:04,719
and moving a greater distance per candle, 
showing a gain in bullish momentum. The  

1315
02:22:04,720 --> 02:22:10,720
increasing size of the candles indicates 
that buyers are becoming more aggressive.

1316
02:22:10,720 --> 02:22:16,560
Momentum Loss can be found when the candles 
start to decrease in size. This suggests that  

1317
02:22:16,560 --> 02:22:23,040
the movement in price is losing strength. If 
you observe that after a series of large bullish  

1318
02:22:23,040 --> 02:22:29,680
candles, the candles begin to shrink in size, 
it could be a warning sign. Shrinking candles  

1319
02:22:29,680 --> 02:22:34,720
suggest that although the trend is still 
upward, the buyers are not as aggressive as  

1320
02:22:34,720 --> 02:22:41,359
before. The distance traveled per candle gets 
shorter, signaling that the buyers are losing  

1321
02:22:41,359 --> 02:22:47,839
control and the bullish momentum is weakening. 
This shift could be due to various reasons,  

1322
02:22:47,840 --> 02:22:53,200
such as traders taking profits after a 
price surge or simply the market running  

1323
02:22:53,200 --> 02:23:00,559
out of steam. When buyers begin to pull back, the 
supply may start to match or exceed the demand,  

1324
02:23:00,560 --> 02:23:06,880
leading to smaller price movements. Momentum 
loss is not only about shrinking candles,  

1325
02:23:06,880 --> 02:23:13,920
but also about where these candles appear. If 
this pattern occurs after a prolonged uptrend  

1326
02:23:13,920 --> 02:23:20,319
at a key resistance level, it could be a strong 
indicator that the trend might reverse or at least  

1327
02:23:20,319 --> 02:23:27,359
stall. This is because at resistance levels, the 
price has historically struggled to move higher,  

1328
02:23:27,359 --> 02:23:33,439
and with weakening momentum, the likelihood 
of breaking through these levels decreases.

1329
02:23:33,439 --> 02:23:36,479
The plan here is to ride the wave of increasing  

1330
02:23:36,479 --> 02:23:41,759
buyer enthusiasm during momentum 
gain phases. On the other hand,  

1331
02:23:41,760 --> 02:23:48,399
noticing a momentum loss with decreasing candle 
sizes could signal a time to be cautious.

1332
